<DOCNO> AP901001-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
thousands of people from alcoholics to 
soldiers are slogging through the nations potato fields in a race 
to salvage the rotting crop and save muscovites from a hungry 
winter 
joining the forced laborers in the muddy trenches of what the 
press has dubbed the potato front are volunteers who are 
lending a hand so they can carry home a sack or two of the starchy 
staple that has vanished from store shelves in the capital 
tatyana shcherbach who was ordered into harvest duties by her 
bosses at the lepes metallurgical factory laughed heartily as her 
three coworkers joked about president mikhail s gorbachev 
weve been wondering whether gorbachev eats potatoes like 
this she said holding up a halfrotten one or if he gets 
potatoes from the states 
her laughter spilled across the collective farms halfplowed 
rows in the village of peshki about 30 miles northwest of moscow 
along the highway to leningrad 
the 44yearold woman giggled saying she and her colleagues had 
concluded gorbachev would opt for the soviet spud because hes 
not the kind of man to eat anything special 
as a stiff wind blew chilled unprotected hands in the 40degree 
temperatures shcherbach said it helps to joke and make fun of 
one another it makes the job much easier and such weather 
requires jokes 
she and about 100 colleagues from the factory plunked the 
potatoes into pails and carried them to large sacks standing in the 
rows many potatoes in the field already were rotten shcherbach 
said holding a shriveled one in her soiled thin cotton gloves 
before discarding it 
drenching rains have turned the fields to mud crippling harvest 
operations for most of september and killing much of the crop 
moscow has only 7 percent of the potato stock it needs for the 
winter 
students and soldiers were drafted into the harvest weeks ago 
and leaders of moscows regional government invited city dwellers 
to go to nearby collective and state farms to help dig potatoes 
with an option to buy them at low prices 
as shcherbach spoke young red army soldiers busily collected 
the 110pound sacks of potatoes and hefted them into the arms of 
compatriots riding atop an open trailer pulled by an old tractor 
wed rather be doing something else admitted pvt taras 
grebnichenko of kiev the soviet union has ordered 23000 soldiers 
into harvest duties in the moscow area 
welcome to the gulag archipelago laughed one of a 
halfdozen soldiers warming themselves at a nearby bonfire 
referring to the alexander solzhenitsyn book about soviet labor 
camps 
the soldiers roasted some potatoes on the embers a blackened 
one was picked from the ashes and handed to a comrade who pulled a 
folded up newspaper containing salt from beneath his tunic 
seasoned it and offered it to eat 
they kidded each other as they passed around the potatoes do 
you know how to speak arabic one joked alluding to the persian 
gulf crisis and possible duty in a drier climate 
the mood was more sullen about 50 yards away where 40 
recovering alcoholics from moscow methodically picked up the 
potatoes under the close supervision of a brigade leader 
alcoholics in the soviet unions treatment centers frequently do 
such forced labor 
working in a different part of the field and espousing a 
different attitude was nikolai g gorodetsky im eager to help 
and get some potatoes as a result because the shelves are picked 
clean he said 
individuals like gorodetsky are entitled to keep every sixth 
sack of potatoes they dig or pay 45 cents for every 22 pounds for 
their entire bounty 
the engineer joined by his wife lyudmilla and teenage son 
sergei said his family would harvest four sacks about 440 pounds 
and give two of them back to the collective farm taking home 220 
pounds at a cost of about 45 
that price is no different than in state stores but long lines 
of shoppers have snapped up all the potatoes in those 
establishments those few potatoes still in moscows markets are 
