<TEXT>
the strategically located korean 
peninsula is in the vortex of rapidly developing new relationships 
that may change the political landscape of northeast asia 
for the first time since the end of world war ii countries that 
have been bitter adversaries and battleground enemies are talking 
to one another delicate relations are being slowly cautiously 
realigned 
northeast asia is unique in that it engages the vital interests 
of four of the worlds great powers the united states the soviet 
union japan and china the tense and bitterly divided korean 
peninsula sits at its geographical heart 
all four countries are involved in and will be affected by 
changes in korea all four governments have an interest in security 
and peace on the peninsula and all four have economic reasons for 
wanting to encourage friendly ties between north and south korea 
the result is a gradual restructuring of alliances some of them 
unthinkable as recently as two or three years ago 
south korea and the soviet union established full diplomatic 
relations on sunday for the first time since russia and the yi 
dynasty broke off ties in 1905 the announcement followed by three 
days north koreas stated intention to open talks on normalizing 
relations with japan 
the two moves are seen as catalysts in breaking down cold war 
barriers and point toward the possibility of eventual recognition 
of the rival koreas by the others allies the united states and 
japan recognizing north korea and beijing and moscow recognizing 
south korea 
the surge in political activity comes as the divided germanys 
unite an event that holds deep emotional significance for all 
koreans who feel shamed at the division of korea 
the mending of decades of distrust between two koreas with 
starkly opposing ideologies is not expected to be quick or easy 
president roh taewoo hopes to see unification by the end of the 
century dissidents and radical students who harp on immediacy say 
it will take five years 
confrontation and tensions continue to hamper the relations 
between the two divided parts of korea said roh said on monday 
but he said new ties will make it impossible for north korea 
alone to resist the tidal wave of change 
prime ministers of the koreas held talks in september the 
highestlevel contact ever between the two nations a second round 
of talks is scheduled for this month 
because of its geography korea long has served both as a buffer 
and an invasion route for its powerful neighbors in the last 
century alone three wars have been fought on korean territory for 
35 years until 1945 korea was occupied by the japanese 
the peninsula was divided in 1945 and in 1950 north korea 
invaded the south launching a threeyear civil war that left more 
than 4 million people killed and wounded a peace treaty was never 
signed 
the border remains tightly sealed distrust and suspicion are 
rampant there is no mail telephone communication or travel 
between the two sides 
the longsought impetus for change has been the need for money 
and technology 
north korea is virtually bankrupt wealthy japan just 350 miles 
away could provide desperately needed capital and technology 
japan could find in north korea cheap labor raw materials and a 
land route into asia 
the soviet union also in need of capital has found in south 
korea a willing investor as well as factories anxious to build and 
market high technology 
the seoul government reportedly expects to sign an agreement for 
more than 2 billion in aid to moscow some also see the soviets 
ties to seoul as bait for japan which has turned down moscows 
overtures for investments 
china longtime ally of north korea needs to expand its 
markets and is expected to open trade offices with seoul before the 
end of the year 
south korea hopes relations with both china and the soviet union 
will stop beijing and moscow from vetoing its attempts to enter the 
united nations 
for its part washington hopes eased tensions will insure 
stability in the region eventually allow a scaleback of 43000 
us troops stationed in south korea and remove an excuse for 
antiamericanism 
for south korea new relations with the soviet union are the 
culmination of a vigorous twoyear campaign to develop ties with 
allies of the north 
the ties between seoul and moscow will have significant 
bearing on the charting of a new world order said kim hakjoon 
a top aide to roh we are seeing new opportunities for progress 
in northeast asia 
</TEXT>
