<TEXT>
when martin meyer of chicago set out 
to join the french foreign legion the legendary fighting force 
enshrined in film and song he faced one big hurdle finding their 
paris outpost 
it took meyer 24 hours of wandering the french capital before he 
stumbled upon fort norgent and told the burly legionnaires inside 
he had come to join up 
i knocked on the gate he recalled they tell you to 
wait 
it may not have been a glorious start to meyers stint in the 
foreign legion whose troops are the veterans of countless battles 
in jungles and deserts the world over their exploits made famous 
in pc wrens novel beau geste 
but now he is a 28yearold corporal and was among the first 
legionnaires to land in saudi arabia as part of the multinational 
force deployed to the region after iraq invaded kuwait 
there are 2300 legionnaires among the french ground troops and 
meyer is one of three americans the legion is 40 percent french 
and 60 percent foreigners culled from 90 nationalities 
like countless hardliving legionnaires before him meyer left 
behind a troubled past 
a native of arvada colo he crisscrossed the united states 
with a mother and two brothers he was the child of a broken home 
he said 
we had a lot of family troubles said meyer ive always 
been the black sheep 
five years ago he said his wife walked out on him in mexico 
mo taking their baby with her 
i just wanted to disappear he said ill never see them 
again 
he had first headd about the foreign legion during a threeyear 
stint with the us air force in west germany that ended in 1981 
and read about it in combat magazines 
after his wife left he said he checked out a book on the 
legion from the public library he applied for a passport and he 
left chicago on a chilly autumn day in 1985 
in some ways meyer was a textbook recruit legion officials say 
most applicants are mavericks who find they just do not fit into 
society false identities are not uncommon nor are past brushes 
with the law murderers and serious criminals are not welcome 
however 
in paris once meyer had passed an initial round of interviews 
with the legion they took away his possessions and shipped him 
south to their headquarters in aubagne there he underwent a 
twoweek round of physical and mental tests and relentless 
questioning 
about half of the wouldbe volunteers are accepted they agree 
to stay in the force for at least five years they learn french 
and undergo difficult even brutal physical training 
legionnaires get regular army pay afterward they are 
recommended for french citizenship 
formed in 1831 by king louisphilippe the legion lost some of 
its luster in recent years with frances bruising defeats in 
algeria and vietnam but a modernday legionnaire is still likely 
to see action in frances farflung former possessions 
six months after joining meyer was sent to the former french 
colony of djibouti on the red sea then the african nations of 
chad and gabon 
the legionnaires arriving in saudi arabia are heading for the 
front in armoured personal carriers with some light artillery 
we are very im losing my english said meyer searching 
for the word expendable we are the frontline forces 
he has never seen combat he hopes he will in the saudi desert 
i love it this is what we trained for he said i just 
hope they let us do it 
he does have one worry chemical weapons iraq is known to 
possess them and has used them in combat 
but we have to be ready for anything he said if its a 
mantoman trooptotroop battle we will win 
