mahal about 110 miles south of new delhi 
the indian express newspaper said the conversions were prompted 
by clashes in june with uppercaste hindus near agra 
seven people were killed and 110 were injured in the threeday 
riots that began when a wedding procession was attacked by 
uppercaste hindus protesting the noise 
welcoming the converts a local politician sangh priya gautam 
said buddhism was the only religion based on realism and 
equality press trust of india reported 
the converts called harijans were below the complex hindu 
caste system that determines a persons social standing by birth 
and often affects economic position 
harijans are not assigned any caste making them 
untouchables for the higherborn hindus in many indian 
villages the socalled outcastes are not allowed to use umbrellas 
or wear shoes when in an uppercaste neighborhood 
despite official government rejection of the caste system it is 
prevalent in rural india efforts by harijans to assert their 
rights have often led to clashes with the upper castes 
university students who belong to upper castes have also been 
protesting some by selfimmolation an august government decree 
setting aside 49 percent of civil service jobs for lowcaste 
workers 
saturdays ceremony took place while hindus celebrated one of 
their most important festivals the dusshera which marks the 
victory of good over evil 
about 60 monks supervized the conversion the largest since 
1981 when about 300000 lowcaste hindus embraced buddhism in the 
western town of nagpur 
there are about 47 million buddhists in india comprising less 
than 1 percent of indias 800 million people 
hindus make up about 82 percent of the population 
buddhism which does not have castes was founded in india as a 
religion and philosophy about 2500 years ago by siddhartha 
gautama it teaches the practice of meditation and observance of 
moral principles 
