<TEXT>
mammograms would be cheaper and perhaps more 
effective in preventing breast cancer deaths if the united states 
did not have as many mammography machines researchers reported 
today 
the researchers from the national institutes of health and the 
food and drug administration reported in the annals of internal 
medicine that the country has 3 times more mammography machines 
than it needs 
martin l brown of the national cancer institute the reports 
lead author said the high number of the xray screening devices 
reduces the number of patients per machine keeping costs high 
and with so many facilities using the machnnes its unlikely 
they can afford the recordkeeping and followup care that make 
mammography useful in preventing deaths from breast cancer he 
said 
an accompanying editorial by dr alvin mushlin of the university 
of rochester medical center also warned that the oversupply of 
mammography units may ultimately lead to a situation in which 
more care does not mean better care and it certainly is unlikely 
to mean more costeffective care 
researchers estimate that each year 150000 american women 
develop breast cancer and 44000 die of the disease 
breast cancer rates could be lowered about 30 percent if women 
received mammograms as recommended by the national cancer 
institute according to earlier studies about onethird of women 
eligible get regular screenings the centers for disease control 
reported 
although an estimated 10000 mammography machines were installed 
by 1990 the actual need is only about 2600 the authors said 
if doctors lowered the average cost of a screening test from 
100 to 50 by using fewer machines the country could save 763 
million a year in health costs brown said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

