<TEXT>
a state law requiring hospitals and clinics 
to arrange for the burial or cremation of aborted fetuses instead 
of flushing them into the sewer system became effective today 
the measure considered the nations strictest was strongly 
opposed by medical groups which contended that it added costs and 
risks to disposal abortion rights advocates charged it might have 
a chilling effect on women considering an abortion 
i think it says that in minnesota we regard the remains of 
unborn babies with dignity and not something to be thrown down the 
sewer system said brian gibson director of prolife action 
ministries of the twin cities 
gibsons group helped initiate the law by exhibiting an aborted 
fetus it said came from a clinics garbage container the clinic 
denied it 
dave feinwachs general counsel for the minnesota hospital 
association complained that the law makes illegal the common 
sanitary practice of flushing fetal tissue into the sewer system 
storing tissue in barrels of formaldehyde and trucking it 
around is just plain stupid he said 
thomas webber executive director of planned parenthood of 
minnesota said the law is designed to give the inference that 
the state of minnesota is saying to women you just committed 
murder you just killed a little person 
the law also prohibits the burning of fetal tissue in hospital 
incinerators another common disposal method the law applies to 
miscarriages as well as induced abortions it carries up to 90 days 
in jail and a 700 fine 
planned parenthood sued to block the 1987 law contending it was 
vague and would stifle abortions by adding costs and psychological 
trauma a federal judge agreed in 1989 but a federal appeals court 
overruled him in august 
rebecca palmer a planned parenthood laywer said the group 
decided against appealing to the us supreme court because of the 
high courts 1989 decision giving states greater leeway to restrict 
abortion 
laws regulations or city ordinances in at least 15 other states 
have called for special disposal of fetal remains said thomas 
strahan of the rutherford institute in charlottesville va a 
nonprofit legal services organization 
but some of those laws were struck down as unconstitutional and 
others do not have penalties or are too vague to be enforced he 
said 
minnesotas law is the most comprehensive and definitive 
strahan said 
hospitals and abortion clinics have complained to the health 
department that some funeral homes and cemeteries have refused to 
take fetal remains fearing pickets from antiabortion groups 
dan mcinerney deputy state health commissioner said his 
department will approve alternatives only when burial and cremation 
prove impossible to obtain 
weve been advising our members to cooperate said gary 
larson executive director of the minnesota funeral directors 
association but on the other hand a funeral home is not 
responsible for handling fetal tissue we are in business to 
provide funerals for families of people who die 
dale carlson president of the minnesota association of cemetery 
officials denied there is any widespread opposition to taking 
fetuses 
its really not for us to pick and choose or question how they 
specimens for burial got to that point he said 
minnesota averages 16000 to 17000 abortions annually and 
feinwachs said it is unclear how many miscarriages there are its 
also unclear what the additional costs will be 
whatever it is its a waste of money because its 
unnecessary he said now we are faced with the very sensitive 
dilemma of telling them women who have miscarried that theres 
this extra cost for a funeral 
</TEXT>
