<TEXT>
patrick white a britishborn writer 
whose nobel prizewinning fiction drew inspiration from life in 
australias outback has died his literary agent said today white 
was 78 
barbara mobbs whites agent said the author died sunday of 
respiratory failure after a lengthy illness 
white a rancherturnedwriter frequently set his novels in the 
outback considered one of this countrys leading authors his 
works were required reading in many high schools and universities 
he was awarded the nobel prize in literature in 1973 
the sydney morning herald today eulogized white as the 
greatest australian writer to date by far 
he transcended the cultural divisions from the past he was 
both contemporary and a traditionalist an australian and 
simultaneously an international writer the newspaper said 
the poet playwright and novelist was born on may 28 1912 in 
london he was educated at kings college cambridge 
he later worked as a jackaroo or rancher in new south 
wales state and then returned to england to study languages at 
cambridge 
he served as an intelligence officer in the royal air force in 
the middle east during world war ii 
since the war my life has been practically uneventful 
white wrote for a 1955 reference work on authors i returned to 
australia to a small property in castle hill a town about 25 miles 
from sydney where i breed schnauzers saanen goats cultivate 
olives and citrus fruit grow vegetables and live more or less off 
my own produce 
his first novel happy valley published in 1939 was 
awarded the australian literary society gold medal his 1955 novel 
the tree of man won the same prize 
his novel eye of the storm portrayed the final days of an 
elderly woman whose greedy relatives returned to europe to await 
her death eye of the storm also explored australians 
attitudes toward their european cultural roots 
essayist margaret b lewis once wrote white is a writer who 
makes serious demands of his readers straining prose to the utmost 
poetic limits putting severe pressure on syntax and vocabulary and 
stretchin credence to an unusual degree in his search for the 
transcendent in the lives of his idiosyncratic characters 
whites plays included the 1977 big toys about the 
governments uranium mining policies signal driver in 1982 
and netherwood the following year he also wrote a screenplay 
a book of verse and a 1981 autobiography flaws in the glass a 
selfportrait 
critics described his autobiography as a merciless 
selfexamination it omitted his acts of generosity such as his 
support for aboriginal education and his use of nobel money to 
establish an award for older australian writers 
in flaws in the glass white wrote frankly of his 
homosexuality a subject he also had addressed in the twyborn 
affair in 1979 
there was no immediate word of survivors a spokesman said 
funeral arrangements were being kept private 
</TEXT>
