<TEXT>
indias supreme court today ordered the 
government to halt its job quota program the court said it hoped 
its temporary injunction would stop a wave of student protests and 
suicides 
the fivejudge panel also advanced the date for hearing 
arguments on the legality of the program by two weeks to oct 25 
press trust of india reported 
the court said the government could continue preparations for 
carrying out the plan which reserves 27 percent of federal jobs 
for lowcaste hindus 
the government is assembling a list of thousands of castes which 
will qualify for preference in job applications another 22 percent 
already are set aside for the lowest strata in the rigid hierarchy 
of indian society tribespeople and the socalled untouchables 
acting chief justice ranganath mishra said he hoped that peace 
would be restored while the issue was being studied by the nations 
highest court the temporary injunction will remain in effect until 
the supreme court rules on the legality of the quotas 
at least 70 people have died in demonstrations against the plan 
announced aug 7 by prime minister vp singh about 20 were 
uppercaste students who committed suicide by selfimmolation or 
poisoning after claiming they were victimized by the plan 
in parliament the government faced a separate problem when it 
failed to pass a constitutional amendment extending federal rule in 
the northern state of punjab where sikh militants are fighting for 
independence 
the state govenment in punjab was dismissed in 1987 and replaced 
by federal rule which the constitution limits to three years 
amending the document requires a twothirds majority 
in a surprise move aimed at embarassing the government the 
opposition congress party refused to support the bill leaders of 
all the parties were summoned to the speakers chambers to find a 
way out of the impasse 
singh 10monthold government suffered another setback when the 
speaker of the legislature agreed to hold a debate on a motion 
seeking to censure the government for mishandling the student 
protest 
the motion if passed would put pressure on the government to 
quit said kewal verma a parliamentary analyst 
there is no legal obligation on the part of the government to 
resign but it would amount to its defeat in moral terms said 
verma 
in the parliament congress party members accused singh of being 
obstinate for refusing to suspend or reconsider the affirmative 
action plan down down resign resign they shouted as singh 
stood up to speak he was prevented from addressing the house 
cant you see there is blood in your hands said congress 
lawmaker ajit panja some members advanced menacingly at singh but 
were stopped by colleagues you are a bloodstained politician 
said panja 
former congress minister vasant sathe said he was beginning a 
fast unto death until singh stops police terror on the 
students 
in the northern town of jammu 17yearold student sandeep 
sharma set himself on fire today in the latest suicide bid to 
protest the job quotas he suffered thirddegree burns over most of 
his body 
at least 20 students have died in the past 12 days from 
selfinflicted injuries most left notes blaming singhs job 
policy in addition 50 people have died by police gunfire in 
street battles 
singh announced the policy aug 7 to increase the quota for 
lowcaste indians in government jobs to 49 percent saying he was 
seeking social justice for indians discriminated against because of 
the social station of their birth 
uppercaste students say reverse discrimination will deprive 
them of government jobs for which they are better qualified 
singh also is facing a revolt in his own janata dal party over 
the issue 
former deputy prime minister devi lal resigned his parliamentary 
seat on sunday and dissidents called for a new party leader but 
the partys parliament bloc a key forum gave singh a vote of 
confidence 
allied parties whose tacit support keep the governing coalition 
in power also have attacked the governments handling of the 
demonstrations although none has criticized the idea of reserving 
jobs for deprived classes 
