<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether us businesses break the law if they discriminate against 
americans they employ outside the country 
the justices setting the stage for an important ruling said 
they will decide whether congress intended a major antibias law to 
reach beyond the nations borders 
a federal appeals court ruling in a case from saudi arabia 
said the law has no effect outside the country but federal trial 
judges have ruled in several other cases that the law does apply 
abroad 
the justices acted on appeals by the bush administration and a 
former oil industry employee 
ali boureslan of el paso texas is a naturalized citizen who 
was born in lebanon an engineer boureslan began working in 1979 
for aramco services co the houstonbased subsidiary of the 
arabian american oil co aramco 
he was transferred to saudi arabia in 1980 and alleges that 
once there he was subjected to racial and religious discrimination 
after filing a complaint with the federal equal employment 
opportunity commission boureslan sued aramco services and its 
parent company he charged them with violating an antibias law 
called title vii of the civil rights act of 1964 
the two companies contested the suit contending that title vii 
does not apply to alleged discrimination outside the united states 
a federal trial judge agreed and threw out the suit last 
february the entire 5th us circuit court of appeals upheld the 
dismissal by a 95 vote 
in urging the justices to reverse the appeals court ruling eeoc 
and justice department lawyers said such a limiting interpretation 
of title viis reach would withdraw the acts protection from the 
many americans who spend a portion of their careers abroad 
the government appeal relied heavily on an exemption written 
into the law one that says the law shall not apply to an 
employer with respect to employment of aliens outside any state 
that exemption would be entirely superfluous if the act did 
not apply abroad in the first place the government appeal 
contended 
but the 5th circuit court said the exemption could be read to 
reflect a congressional intent to provide title vii coverage to 
aliens employed within but not outside the united states 
the cases are eeoc vs arabian american oil co 891838 and 
boureslan vs arabian american oil co 891845 
