argentine president carlos menem said today that 
iraqs saddam hussein has to be stopped but declined to say 
whether he was prepared to send argentine forces into battle to 
force iraq out of kuwait 
president bush conferred separately this morning with menem and 
uruguay president luis alberto lacalle thanking both latin leaders 
for their solidarity in the international stand against iraq for 
invading kuwait 
menem also assured bush that he has completely deactivated a 
secret condor missile development program that past argentine 
military governments had pursued 
the united states has feared that the program could make it 
easier for hostile regimes in libya and elsewhere to get their 
hands on such mediumrange missiles 
menem questioned about whether he was prepared to commit his 
forces to fight against iraq said we have sent this group of 
professional officers to consolidate and give support to the 
embargo that was decided upon by the un 
but i cannot give you an opinion on something that has not 
yet happened he said 
did bush give menem the impression that war was likely 
no no no said menem adding that they did not discuss 
the possibility of war but he said we have agreed that 
iraqs president has to be stopped 
menem recently dispatched two warships to the persian gulf 
becoming the first and so far only latin leader to commit forces to 
the international armada 
bush called menem courageous and said the united states 
is very grateful to you not just for his stand in the gulf 
crisis but his economic reforms as well 
lacalle told bush that uruguay has been really hurt by 
honoring the sanctions 
we had 30 million of meat mutton ready to be sent to iraq 
under recently negotiated contracts he said its two punches 
the oil and the cutting of those contracts 
uruguay is asking the united nations for some of the 
international aid that will be distributed to third countries that 
bear the brunt of the effort to isolate iraq 
uruguay is a country that has paid a serious price for 
complying with the sanctions assistant secretary of state 
bernard aronson said afterwards we would hope that their claim 
would be looked on sympathetically and seriously 
on the condor missiles aronson said menem told bush it had been 
completely deactivated 
we certainly take menem at his word said the state 
department official thats a major step in reducing the threat 
of missile proliferation 
