<TEXT>
the states department of archives and 
history is opening up windows to the past by offering the public a 
way to trace the roots of former slaves 
the department is establishing a computer index of the first 
labor contracts that onetime slaves in mississippi entered into as 
free people in 1865 and 1866 
we plan to make the information available to the public in 
february said ht holmes director of the departments library 
division the computer searches would be free 
librarians would guide families through thousands of labor 
contracts kept by the freedmens bureau formed by congress after 
the civil war to ensure former slaves were treated fairly holmes 
said 
the contracts detailed the former slaves names where they were 
working their bosses terms of their pay and in some instances 
their general health 
the washingtonbased documents are extensively used said judy 
thorne a consultant at the national archives 
a lot of people who are doing southern history are interested 
in them a lot of people interested in afroamerican history use 
them and a few military historians are interested in them because 
the military was running the project thorne said 
the freedmens bureau supervised abandoned or confiscated land 
issued rations of clothing and medicine established hospitals 
monitored working conditions recorded new and old marriages and 
set up schools 
mississippi had 436631 slaves in 1860 out of a total population 
of 791305 according to the mississippi statistical summary of 
population for 1860 
