<TEXT>
the supreme court said today it will try to 
clarify what authority police have to pursue and detain people who 
run away after seeing police 
the justices agreed to consider reinstating the cocaine 
conviction and 68month sentence of an oakland calif youth who a 
state court said was chased and caught unlawfully by police 
california attorney general john van de kamp argues that the 
state court ruling limits too severely police authority in such 
situations 
two members of the oakland police departments drug task force 
were on patrol april 18 1988 when they saw four young men 
standing by a parked car the youths saw the officers when the 
patrol car was about 40 yards from them they immediately ran away 
and the parked car sped off 
the officers who said they suspected they had interrupted a 
drug transaction decided to give chase officer jerry pertoso took 
a course that resulted in his running straight into a youth 
identified as hodari d 
initially looking over his shoulder the youth did not see the 
officer until they were about 10 feet apart pertoso testified that 
the youth then threw away what turned out to be a rock of cocaine 
pertoso stopped hodari d forced him to the ground and 
handcuffed him the officer then retrieved the cocaine 
hodari d was found to have possessed cocaine by a juvenile 
court judge who ordered him placed in an appropriate county 
facility for five years and eight months 
a state appeals court however overturned the youths 
conviction 
the appeals court ruled that the police chase undertaken 
without a reasonable suspicion that a crime had been committed 
amounted to an unlawful detention 
the appeals court also ruled that hodari ds abandonment of the 
cocaine rock was a direct result of the unlawful detention so the 
drug should not have been used as evidence against him 
the constitutions fourth amendment generally requires police to 
obtain a court warrant before conducting searches or making 
arrests courts have allowed some warrantless searches and arrests 
but only when police do not have time to get a warrant and have 
probable cause or a reasonable suspicion to suspect a crime 
the california supreme court refused to hear the states appeal 
last march 15 
in the appeal acted on today van de kamp argued that a police 
chase never can be a detention 
when a citizen exercises his constitutional right to leave the 
vicinity of a police officer the former is not detained until the 
latter has forcibly restrained him the attorney general said 
in deciding a michigan case in 1988 the nations highest court 
said officers sometimes may chase someone who starts running at the 
sight of them even if they have no reason to suspect criminal 
conduct 
but the court left undecided whether police pursuit ever could 
amount to a seizure 
the case is california vs hodari d 891632 
</TEXT>
