<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to hear an 
appeal by a former west virginia legislator convicted of extorting 
money from a group of foreigntrained doctors and not reporting it 
as taxable income 
the court said it will consider overturning a 50000 fine and 
threeyear suspended prison sentence and probation for robert l 
mccormick a former member of the west virginia house of delegates 
mccormick who represented an economically depressed coalmining 
region suffering from a shortage of doctors was a longtime 
supporter of legislation allowing foreigntrained physicians to 
practice in underserved areas of the state without meeting full 
licensing requirements 
federal prosecutors said that in 1984 mccormick told john 
vandergrift a lobbyist for the doctors that his reelection 
campaign was expensive and that he had not heard from the 
physicians 
vandergrift then delivered an envelope to mccormick containing 
nine 100 bills from dr ernesto manual head of the group called 
the coalfield health care association prosecutors said mccormick 
received additional cash payments bringing the total to 4300 
mccormick sponsored legislation in 1985 to give permanent 
medical licenses to experienced foreigntrained doctors who failed 
to get passing grades on licensing exams the doctors had been 
practicing with temporary permits 
mccormick was convicted of extorting 900 from the doctors and 
not reporting it as taxable income the jury deadlocked on counts 
of the indictment charging him with taking additional payoffs 
the former lawmaker said the money was a campaign contribution 
and said he did not report it to the internal revenue service 
because the cash reimbursed him for expenses 
the 4th us circuit court of appeals in upholding the 
conviction in february ruled there was substantial evidence for 
the jury to conclude mccormick was guilty of extortion 
the appeals court said it is not necessary to show there is a 
quid pro quo exchange of money for government favors to prove a 
violation of the federal hobbs act outlawing extortion 
such a quid pro quo may be present in an extortion but as 
long as the use of official power is the basis for the extortion 
then it is not an essential element of the crime the appeals 
court said 
the appeals court also noted that west virginia law forbids cash 
campaign contribution of more than 50 
mccormicks acceptance of money in violation of state law is 
additional evidence of extortion the appeals court said 
it also rejected mccormicks argument that the money was not 
taxable personal income but reimbursement for campaign expenses 
the jury had ample evidence to conclude the 900 was not a 
legitimate campaign contribution and therefore to decide it was 
taxable the appeals court said 
the case is mccormick vs us 891918 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

