<TEXT>
the supreme court today rejected a challenge 
to the federal law barring some state and local government 
employees from being political candidates 
the court without comment let stand connecticuts loss of 
about 150000 in federal welfare money because two welfare workers 
ran for office 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for connecticut argued 
that the federal law known as the hatch act violates the 
constitutionally protected right of political association and 
tramples state sovereignty 
a federal trial judge and the 2nd us circuit court of appeals 
rejected those arguments previously 
the hatch act limits not only the political activities of 
federal employees but also those of state and local government 
workers employed by agencies that receive federal loans or grants 
the act bars federal employees from taking an active part in 
political management or in political campaigns it originally 
imposed such a ban for some state and local government workers but 
was narrowed so that now only political candidacy is barred for 
them 
in 1985 wayne camillieri worked for the connecticut department 
of human resources in a position involved with federally funded 
programs camillieri since 1983 had been a member of the hartford 
city council 
the us merit systems protection board in mid1985 informed 
camillieri that the hatch act prohibited him from seeking 
reelection to the city council if he remained in his state 
government job 
camillieri nevertheless ran for reelection he was defeated in 
the democratic primary 
the board subsequently ordered the state agency to remove 
camillieri from his position warning that failure to do so within 
30 days would result in the withholding of federal loans and grants 
equal to two years pay for camillieri 
the state agency refused to remove him and 90150 in federal 
funds were withheld 
jack winkleman also was an employee of the connecticut 
department of human resources involved in federally funded programs 
when in 1986 he was endorsed by the republican party as a candidate 
for probate judge 
winkleman ran for the office while holding his state agency job 
but he was defeated in the general election 
the federal board later ordered that winkleman be removed from 
his job threatening to withhold federal money equal to two years 
of his pay if he were not within 30 days 
the agency balked and 60896 in federal money was withheld 
state officials sought review in federal court but the 
withholding of funds was upheld by us district judge jose 
cabranes 
citing past supreme court rulings cabranes said 
infringements upon the ability of government employees be they 
federal or state to be candidates for elective office do not 
violate the first amendment 
he also rejected arguments that the federal governments action 
against the state violated the 10th amendments granting of state 
sovereignty 
the appeals court upheld cabranes ruling in a brief order last 
january 
state officials then sought help from the nations highest 
court 
the case is connecticut vs us merit systems protection board 
891582 
</TEXT>
