<TEXT>
frank snepp the excia operative turned 
author lost a supreme court appeal today in his fight with the spy 
agency over getting prepublication clearance for some of his work 
the court without comment left intact rulings that put the 
burden on snepp not the cia to seek a courts help if 
disagreements arise over what the agency is entitled to censor 
snepp worked for the central intelligence agency from 1968 to 
1976 working either in vietnam or on vietnam matters at cia 
headquarters in langley va 
in 1977 snepp published a critical account of the final days of 
us involvement in vietnam the book decent interval was 
published without first having been submitted for agency 
preclearance 
the supreme court in 1980 ruled that snepps publication of the 
book was a breach of his employment contract with the cia and 
ordered that he forfeit all proceeds from the book to the agency 
the high court also ruled that the cia could continue to require 
snepp to submit any agencyrelated writings for prepublication 
approval 
a footnote to the 1980 decision said allowing such preclearance 
was not condoning censorship if snepp in compliance with 
contract had submitted his manuscript for review and the agency 
had found it to contain sensitive material presumably an 
effort would have been made to eliminate harmful disclosures the 
court said 
absent agreement in this respect the agency would have borne 
the burden of seeking an injunction against publication the 
footnote said 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for snepp said that 1980 
footnote overturned what had been the cias policy of forcing 
employees and exemployees to go to court to challenge an agency 
decision not to allow publication of certain material 
prior to the 1980 supreme court ruling in snepps case the 4th 
us circuit court of appeals had ruled that cia employees and 
exemployees should have the responsibility for initiating court 
fights when disputes arise over the agencys preclearance 
procedures 
the current dispute between snepp and the cia stems from his 
submission for preclearance review in 1985 of a potential 
television miniseries called background lawcase story 
after several rounds of negotiations the cia sought just one 
deletion but by that time the television deal had fallen through 
the 4th circuit court last february rejected snepps contention 
that the agency had been obligated to seek a courts help in its 
effort to keep snepp from publishing the submitted manuscript 
the appeals court said the 1980 supreme court footnote did not 
reverse its previous ruling absolving the cia of the responsibility 
of seeking judicial review 
the case is snepp vs us 891853 
