<TEXT>
the supreme court today permitted the random 
drug testing of new york citys 10000 jail guards 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by the guards 
labor union which said the tests violate the officers privacy 
rights 
the new york court of appeals the states highest court upheld 
the city department of corrections drugtesting program by a 43 
vote in may 
the city uses a computer to select 50 guards at random every two 
weeks for urine tests 
the state court said the city has a compelling interest in 
requiring the tests and said the guards who undergo other 
inspections not required of ordinary citizens or other government 
workers have a diminished expectation of privacy 
by choosing to work in the paramilitary milieu of the city 
corrections department guards voluntarily sacrifice certain 
cherished freedoms judge joseph bellacosa wrote for the state 
court he noted that the guards already undergo drug tests apart 
from the random program they challenged when they apply for jobs 
and while they are on probation 
the city also has a big stake in assuring the guards are drug 
free he said 
the prevention detection and resolution of the myriad daily 
crises in this nether world demand the acutest sensory awareness 
undulled by the use of illicit drugs bellacosa said 
chief judge sol wachtler in a strongly worded dissent said the 
state court ruling made an important constitutional right the 
latest casualty in the war on drugs 
union officials for the guards said tests should be required 
only of those the city has reason to believe are using drugs the 
union said the guards do not have direct responsibility for 
protecting the safety of the general public and because they work 
in confined quarters are less likely to be exposed to drugs 
the union noting the citys claim that 12 percent of tenured 
guards and 29 percent of probationary officers use drugs said 
random testing is unwarranted when such a minute proportion of 
the staff may be using drugs 
the supreme court in 1989 upheld mandatory blood and urine tests 
for railroad workers involved in accidents and for us customs 
service employees seeking drugenforcement jobs 
the high court has not ruled specifically on random tests for 
government workers but it repeatedly has denied without comment 
appeals by such employees challenging random tests 
police officers in new york city also must undergo random drug 
tests they did not challenge the tests in court 
new york state officials have not instituted such tests for 
prison guards who have completed probation 
the case is seelig vs koehler 9048 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

