the supreme court today left intact a policy 
that lets federally regulated banks sell insurance 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by insurance 
industry lawyers who said the federal reserve board policy could 
lead banks into the same morass that has befallen the savings and 
loan industry 
the cost to american taxpayers of bailing out the thrift 
institutions recently was estimated at 500 billion the insurance 
officials reminded the court 
the independent insurance agents of america and other groups 
challenged a 1989 federal reserve board order permitting two 
indiana banks acquired by a bank holding company to sell insurance 
the fed said the bank holding company act of 1956 does not bar 
bank holding companies from acquiring bank subsidiaries engaged in 
nonbanking activities 
the board acted after a congressional moratorium had been lifted 
on nonbanking activities by banks 
merchants national corp a bank holding company was granted 
permission by the fed to acquire the anderson banking co and the 
mid state bank of hendricks county in indiana 
anderson bank has sold insurance since the bank opened for 
business in 1916 mid state purchased an insurance agency in 1985 
the ability of bank holding companies to enter risky 
businesses directly threatens to compromise the financial stability 
of bank holding companies insurance industry officials said in 
their high court appeal 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals ruled in november that the 
fed did not exceed its authority in the merchants national case 
the case is independent insurance agents of america vs federal 
reserve system 891620 
