<TEXT>
the supreme court today left intact a ruling 
that usx corp illegally discriminated against blacks at a fairless 
hills pa steel mill 
the justices without comment rejected arguments that a federal 
appeals court flagrantly disregarded a 1989 supreme court 
decision in ruling against the giant manufacturer 
the philadelphiabased 3rd us circuit court of appeals ruled 
that usx formerly known as us steel corp discriminated against 
blacks who applied for nonskilled production and maintenance jobs 
at the steel mill 
the justices then ordered the appeals court to restudy that 
ruling in light of their 1989 decision called wards cove packing 
co vs antonio 
in it the high court made it far more difficult for workers to 
win some jobbias lawsuits 
the courts wards cove ruling was one of several 1989 decisions 
congress is seeking to overcome in a major civil rights bill 
passed in slightly differing versions by both the house and 
senate 
president bush saying he believes the legislation would force 
employers to adopt racial quotas has threatened to veto the bill 
unless considerable changes are made before it reaches his desk 
after reexamining the fairless hills case the 3rd circuit 
court again ruled against usx 
although wards cove may have reduced the employers burden of 
showing a legitimate nondiscriminatory reason for the challenged 
practices we perceive no reason to disturb the district courts 
and our own prior rejection of usxs assertion that its 
practices were not discriminatory the appeals court said 
although wards cove may have relaxed the employers burden to 
rebut the plaintiffs case we do not read the decision as 
requiring us to accept at face value an employers explanations of 
adverse impact of its hiring practices on blacks the appeals 
court added 
a federal judge in 1983 ordered usx to end all discrimination in 
the hiring of production and maintenance employees at the fairless 
hills mill and awarded more than 123 million to those 
represented by a class action lawsuit 
the judge ruled that statistics showing the disparity between 
the percentages of black applicants and black hires proved that usx 
violated a federal antibias law known as title vii of the civil 
rights act of 1964 
the appeals court upheld the judges title vii ruling but 
ordered him to reconsider the monetary award in a way usx lawyers 
said could raise the award to about 30 million 
the fairless hills mill where 7000 to 10000 workers are 
employed at a given time hired 5516 people including 977 blacks 
to production and maintenance jobs in the years 197182 
in those years blacks represented 259 percent of the 
applicants and 176 percent of the hires 
in the appeal acted on today usx lawyers argued that the 3rd 
circuit court flagrantly disregarded the justices mandate by 
giving wards cove only lip service 
the 3rd circuit imposed on usx the burden of proving that 
innocent factors not race caused the bottom line disparities 
rather than merely producing a reasonable business justification 
for the specific employment practice at issue the steel 
companys appeal said 
the case is usx vs green 891816 
</TEXT>
