the supreme court today killed sioux indian 
tribes legal challenges stemming from their loss through us 
treaties of some 27 million acres of land stretching across three 
states 
the court without comment let stand rulings that the tribes 
waited too long to attack a 1972 plan by congress for distributing 
a 6 million settlement between the tribes and the federal 
government 
under that plan the tribes will receive threefourths of the 
money and 1970 descendants who are not themselves tribal members 
will receive onefourth 
the tribes contended in their 1987 lawsuit that they are 
entitled to 100 percent of the 6 million settlement fund and the 
interest it has earned since 1972 
the dispute has its roots in treaties of 1830 and 1851 in which 
the sisseton and wahpeton sioux ceded to the united states vast 
stretches of land in what now is south dakota iowa and minnesota 
the tribes sued the government about 100 years later contending 
that they had not received just compensation the suit was settled 
and congress in 1968 appropriated the money to pay the settlement 
four years later congress devised the distribution plan but the 
tribes did not challenge it in court until 1987 when the bureau of 
indian affairs indicated the 25 percent set aside for nonmembers 
of the tribes was almost ready for distribution 
us district judge paul hatfield in montana threw out the suit 
ruling that the tribe had only six years to sue after congress 
unveiled the distribution plan 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals upheld the dismissal last 
february and the tribes then sought help from the nations highest 
court 
the case is sissetonwahpeton sioux vs us 892015 
</TEXT>
