the supreme court today asked the bush 
administration for its views of a ruling that could help elect 
blacks to a florida county commission and school board 
the court wants to know what justice department lawyers think 
about an appeal by liberty county fla officials who said a lower 
court went too far in seeking to protect the voting rights of the 
countys black minority 
the governments comments could take months to reach the 
justices who arent expected to say until then whether they will 
grant review to the liberty county case 
the 11th us circuit court of appeals in april ruled in favor 
of black voters challenging the atlarge method of electing 
commissioners and school board members in liberty county 
blacks want members of the two bodies elected by districtwide 
voting one of the five county districts has a majority of 
votingage blacks while blacks comprise only 11 percent of the 
county population 
a black never has been elected to the county commission or 
school board each with five members 
the 11th circuit court stopped short of eliminating countywide 
elections but it sent the case back to a federal judge with 
instructions that may lead to districtwide voting the appeals 
courts 10 members were evenly divided over exactly how to 
implement its ruling 
the decision relied heavily on a 1986 supreme court ruling that 
made it easier for minorities to challenge redistricting plans that 
may dilute their voting strength 
the high court in that case struck down a north carolina 
legislative redistricting plan as a violation of the voting rights 
act 
congress in 1982 amended the 1965 voting rights law to eliminate 
the need for minorities to prove intentional bias when challenging 
districting plans the new law requires only that minorities show 
that districting plans have the effect of diluting their voting 
strength regardless of intent 
in the liberty county case the 11th circuit court said there is 
sufficient evidence the black population is concentrated and 
politically cohesive and that the vote is racially polarized 
an opinion signed by five judges on the 11th circuit said 
black voters have never had an opportunity to elect a black 
representative despite their manifest preference for those black 
candidates that have presented themselves six futile elections is 
enough 
a separate concurring opinion signed by five other judges on the 
appeals court expressed reservations about their colleagues 
opinion they said that opinion would create a right to 
proportional representation for all large compact and cohesive 
minority groups 
the case is liberty county vs solomon 90102 
