negotiators in washington state reached a tentative agreement 
today in the longest teachers strike and new york citys 
85000member union the nations largest averted a walkout just 
hours after its contract expired 
in everett wash negotiators sat down at 1 pm sunday and met 
through the night with three state mediators until reaching an 
agreement about 830 am today said washington education 
association spokesman john cahill 
the proposal was to be brought before teachers in the mukilteo 
school district for ratification this afternoon cahill said he 
declined to release details of the agreement until it was presented 
to the districts 460 teachers the mukilteo strike began aug 30 
and classes were to start sept 5 key issues included class size 
teacher assignment and transfer policies school decisionmaking 
panels and pay for extra time responsibility and incentives 
in new york the city and its teachers union reached tentative 
agreement today on a contract that would raise salaries 55 
percent both sides said 
union spokesman bert shanas said the two sides agreed on a 
oneyear contract and a statement from the school chancellors 
office said the raise would bring starting salaries to 26375 and 
senior salaries to 52750 
the old contract covering 65000 public school teachers and 
20000 other school employees expired at midnight school was in 
session today 
meanwhile the nations largest labor dispute involving teachers 
continued in louisiana the strike by public school teachers 
entered its third week today after union negotiators rejected what 
orleans parish school board officials said was a 13 million 
contract 
in new york neill rosenfeld a spokesman for the united 
federation of teachers said earlier that agreements were reached 
on all noneconomic issues but the two sides were haggling over 
the size of a pay raise 
last week the union rejected the citys offer of a 4 percent 
raise rosenfeld said the city raised that offer but he would not 
how high 
teachers in new york city make a starting salary of 25000 and 
can earn up to 50000 
the new contract will cover employees of about 1000 elementary 
junior high and high schools that serve about 946000 students the 
20000 employees who are not teachers include counselors social 
workers and secretaries 
