<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether unfit prison living conditions may amount to cruel and 
unusual punishment when there is no evidence officials acted 
maliciously 
the justices said they will hear an appeal by an ohio inmate who 
accused officials of being indifferent to overcrowding 
ratinfested kitchens freezing cold oppressive heat and other 
miserable conditions 
the 6th us circuit court of appeals in january threw out a 
suit by pearly wilson a prisoner in the hocking correctional 
facility in nelsonville ohio 
wilson said prison officials violated the eighth amendment to 
the constitution which forbids cruel and unusual punishment 
he said the inmates were in cramped cells subject to excessive 
noise foul lavatories and housed with the physically and mentally 
ill the prison is frigid in winter and stifling in summer he 
added 
but the appeals court said wilson did not demonstrate that 
officials have engaged in persistent malicious cruelty at 
worst the state is guilty of negligence and that does not prove 
any constitutional violation in such circumstances the appeals 
court said 
wilson argued that evidence of deliberate indifference is enough 
to warrant intervention by the federal courts to order states to 
improve living conditions 
he also said the 6th circuit court ruling conflicts with 
decisions by other federal appeals courts 
ohio officials in urging the high court to reject wilsons 
appeal said the inmate filed more that 70 lawsuits against the 
state since 1976 almost all them frivolous or premature 
the officials also said there is ample evidence the state tried 
to improve conditions at the facility 
the case is wilson vs seiter 897376 
</TEXT>
