<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to force 
states to allow some public access to juvenile court hearings or 
records 
the justices without comment let stand kentucky court rulings 
that upheld the mandatory secrecy of the states juvenile courts 
kentuckys policy was challenged in 1988 by the courierjournal 
and louisville times after a newspaper reporter was forbidden to 
see transcripts of a juvenile court hearing 
the dispute arose over the case of a 16yearold youth 
identified in court records by the initials ftp who fatally 
beat another juvenile who lived in the same staterun facility 
after ftp was charged state prosecutors sought to have his 
case transferred out of juvenile court so he could be tried as an 
adult 
in response lawyers for ftp asked a juvenile court judge to 
declare the states transfer law unconstitutional the judge did 
so 
it was the hearing on the transfer laws constitutionality that 
the louisville newspapers sought to attend they later sought to 
obtain transcripts and records from the hearing 
a trial judge ruled that the juvenile court proceedings must 
remain secret and the kentucky court of appeals upheld that ruling 
last year 
the kentucky supreme court refused to hear the newspapers 
appeal last april 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for the newspapers argued 
that past rulings by the nations highest court established a 
presumption of openness in criminal trials and pretrial 
proceedings 
there is simply no reason why proceedings which the 
constitution would require to be presumptively open if the accused 
was an 18yearold can be mandatorily closed when the accused is 
17 the appeal said 
juvenile courts in kentucky are not required or even allowed 
to consider closure on a casebycase basis inquiring into the 
existence and intensity of interests supporting closure it 
added 
the case is courierjournal vs ftp 90107 
</TEXT>
