live in west berlin 
we wanted very much to be out here said sven bein 22 an 
east berliner who also was released from rummelsburg on monday 
petermann who said he was convicted of breaking into a house 
and given a severe sentence because of his political views said 
the amnesty is a great chance to start over 
im for unification said petermann who served 20 months of 
his sentence i never thought it would happen so fast 
heyse bein and petermann were among five youthful offenders 
freed monday from the 400inmate prison 
lawmakers feuded bitterly over the amnesty plan before adopting 
it late friday their last act before meeting for a final time 
tuesday to officially dissolve east germany 
the amnesty was meant to help people who were given unjustly 
harsh sentences by the former communist government which often 
used sentences for petty crimes to punish people who resisted the 
rigidly controlled social system 
naturally all of these people are very pleased said helmut 
raschdorff an official at rummelsburg prison 
he said he expects 115 inmates at the prison to fall under the 
amnesty program and hundreds of others nationwide each will be 
released after serving twothirds of his sentence 
the amnesty is the second since the communist government was 
ousted last autumn early this year scores of political prisoners 
were released 
the weeks of debate over the latest amnesty program coincided 
with uprisings at prisons across east germany inmates occupied 
prison rooftops and staged hunger strikes to demand amnesty 
the government of a united germany still has to deal with 
perhaps an even more senstive topic whether to grant amnesty to 
the spies and secret police agents from the former communist 
government 
