the us supreme courts rejection monday of an 
appeal by three white defendants in the howard beach racial death 
case closes off only one avenue of appeal a defense attorney says 
there are some new trial issues which we will be exploring 
said lawyer charles weintraub 
the court made no comment when it let stand the manslaughter and 
assault convictions of jon lester scott kern and jason ladone 
weintraub had argued they were wrongly limited in excluding blacks 
as trial jurors 
new yorks highest court rejected the argument last march 
the issues were significant but obviously the court is not 
prepared to address those issues at this time weintraub said 
there are some other issues that will be addressed in new trial 
motions 
he refused to discuss what the new issues would be 
on dec 19 1986 a car carrying four black men broke down in 
the predominantly white howard beach section of the borough of 
queens 
three of the men michael griffith cedric sandiford and 
timothy grimes left the car to seek assistance 
the three were attacked by a gang of white teenagers including 
lester kern and ladone according to trial testimony 
the youths chased griffith onto a highway where he was struck 
and killed by a car sandiford was beaten with a baseball bat and 
tree limbs 
the case galvanized black activists in new york in the weeks 
that followed police reported a sharp increase in racial violence 
in the city several fights between blacks and whites were 
punctuated by cries of howard beach howard beach 
during the 1987 trial of lester kern and ladone prosecutors 
complained that the defense lawyers were using their peremptory or 
automatic challenges of potential jurors to exclude all blacks 
in response to the prosecutors complaints the trial judge 
justice thomas demakos barred the defendants lawyers from using 
their automatic challenges to exclude potential jurors because of 
their race 
defense lawyers argued unsuccessfully that prosecutors were 
using their automatic challenges to keep whites off the jury 
the states highest court upheld the three mens convictions 
after ruling that defendants lawyers in all criminal cases may be 
barred from excluding potential jurors because of their race 
the us supreme court in 1986 barred prosecutors from doing 
that ruling that such exclusions are unconstitutional but the 
justices never have said the us constitution imposes such a 
prohibition on defense lawyers 
the state courts ruling appeared to rely solely on the new york 
constitution 
lawyers for lester kern and ladone said the state court ruling 
was an unwarranted expansion of the supreme courts 1986 decision 
the appeal said the new york constitution as interpreted by the 
state court should be declared a violation of the us 
constitutions protections for criminal defendants fairtrial 
rights 
lester was sentenced to up to 30 years in prison kern to up to 
18 years and ladone to up to 15 years weintraub said all have 
begun serving time 
