the house passed legislation monday to upgrade 
security at airlines and airports including directing the 
government to develop guidelines for warning passengers of 
terrorist threats 
never again do we want a situation where the insiders had 
notification but the rest of the world didnt said rep sherwood 
boehlert rny if in the future there is a credible threat 
there will be a mechanism for notification so that people can have 
a choice 
the bill approved on a voice vote without dissent would put 
into law the reforms recommended in may by a sevenmember 
presidential commission that investigated the 1988 bombing of pan 
am flight 103 over lockerbie scotland 
the legislation would require the justice department and federal 
aviation administration to develop guidelines for notifying both 
the public and airplane crews of bomb or other security threats 
airlines airports and travel agents would be required to relay 
any security threat immediately to government officials 
the faa also would be required to hire federal security managers 
at highrisk domestic airports and foreign security liaisons at 
those overseas airline and airport employees with access to 
security areas would have to undergo background checks and new 
training 
to coordinate the activities the legislation establishes a new 
assistant secretarys position in the transportation department for 
security and a similar new assistant administrators post at the 
faa 
it would provide the families of the victims aboard pan am 103 
the same tax relief provided to families of government employees 
aboard the flight which exploded dec 21 1988 killing a total of 
270 people aboard and on the ground 
the state department would be required to negotiate agreements 
with other nations to achieve the enhanced security measures at 
foreign airports and domestic airlines would have to provide the 
department with a passenger manifest within three hours after a 
terrorist incident 
the parts of the bill changing the state departments airline 
and airport security programs were approved last week by the senate 
foreign relations committee 
many of the measures already have been adopted by the 
government the bush administration contends the legislation is not 
needed 
