<DOCNO> AP901001-0161 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a twoyear study of wic operations in five 
states showed monday the supplemental feeding program can reduce 
medical costs of caring for lowincome pregnant women and their 
babies 
the study of the special supplemental food program for women 
infants and children was ordered by congress in 1987 to help 
determine savings in medicaid costs during the first 60 days after 
birth 
typically the wic program provides improved nutrition for poor 
women during pregnancy and for them and their infants after birth 
from its beginning in 1972 the wic program has grown to a 21 
billion operation this year with an enrollment of 45 million women 
and children medicaid is a joint federal and state program that 
covers medical costs of lowincome people 
the 11 million study was done for the departments food and 
nutrition service by mathematica policy research inc of princeton 
nj 
department officials said the study strongly indicated that 
wic participation during pregnancy is associated with reduced 
medicaid costs and increased birth weight 
the study involved births and costs in florida minnesota north 
carolina south carolina and texas over periods in 1987 and 1988 
among the findings were increased birth weights and reduced 
medicaid costs involving the women and their babies 
however the study cautioned that there are considerable 
variations among the wic and medicaid programs operated by 
individual states and that situations are changing rapidly 
these problems are compounded by the exclusion of other 
indigent care costs from the study which means only a partial 
picture of the healthcare costs of lowincome women and newborns 
is available it said 
even so the benefits of wic participation by medicaid 
recipients were so clearly demonstrated in all five study states 
with all their population and program differences that a 
nationwide in 1987 would have shown positive benefits the report 
said 
looking to the future researchers said medicaid expansion is 
allowing a higherincome group of pregnant women to enroll and that 
many of those are likely to participate in wic 
conversely aggressive outreach and improved eligibility 
procedures may bring a higherrisk group of pregnant women into the 
medicaid and the wic programs the report said the net effect 
of these enrollment changes on estimates of wic benefits is 
uncertain 
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter said in a statement that 
the study reaffirms the success of the wic program and 
underscores our emphasis on serving pregnant women and infants as 
wics top priority 
yeutter said that in 1974 as an assistant secretary of 
agriculture he cut the ribbon launching the first wic program 
facility in pineville ky 
</TEXT>
