<TEXT>
energy department officials raised more 
questions than they answered monday about whether an ohio atomic 
weapons facility would permanently stop producing uranium and shift 
to cleaning up decades of radioactive wastes 
henson moore the departments deputy secretary first announced 
during a briefing with reporters that a decision had been made to 
never produce uranium again at the fernald plant near 
cincinnati 
instead he said the plant would concentrate on cleanup and 
development of cleanup technologies that also might be used at 
other weapons facilities with contamination problems 
within hours however a department spokesman disavowed moores 
characterization and said no decision on production would be made 
until january the department said that management at fernald had 
been shifted to the doe office in charge of cleanup activities 
the plant which faces a major cleanup problem from past lax 
production procedures has not produced weapons grade uranium since 
july 1989 the 1000 plant employees have been awaiting word on 
whether production would ever resume 
some fear a shift away from production eventually would shut 
down the facility 
moore raised the issue of uranium production at fernald in 
opening remarks at a briefing with reporters saying he had wanted 
to take the opportunity to disclose that energy secretary james 
watkins had decided making permanent what has been de facto for 
about a year 
it fernald will never produce uranium again moore said 
although not contesting what moore had said department 
spokesmen later said an actual decision by the department on the 
production question at fernald is not expected to be made until 
january 
were probably on the road to closing down production said 
department spokesman bill griffin the decision will be made in 
january whether to at any point resume production or permanently 
turn the facility over to a cleanup mode 
dan darmond a spokesman for moore later also acknowledged 
that a decision on the production issue at fernald is not 
completely finalized but said the department was planning to 
stop uranium production at the ohio facility 
uranium production has been suspended since july 1989 because of 
the facilities environmental problems including widespread 
contamination as a result of past lax production practices 
moore said he didnt anticipate that a permanent halt in 
production would cause job losses at fernald instead the work at 
the 1000acre complex 18 miles from cincinnati would focus 
exclusively on cleanup safely packaging contaminated materials and 
developing new cleanup technologies he said 
the fernald plant was opened in 1951 to process uranium for 
atomic weapons the cost of cleaning up hazardous materials at the 
plant has been estimated at 1 billion to 5 billion 
stored at the plant are more than 500000 metric tons of 
radioactive wastes dating from current plant operations to the 
world war iiera manhattan project to develop the atomic bomb 
