the supreme court on monday agreed to review a 
1 million legal fee that the seller of a louisiana television 
station was ordered to pay in a breachofcontract case 
the court said it will examine the power of federal judges to 
order such payments 
the case stems from a 1983 agreement in which nasco inc a 
tennessee company signed a contract to buy kplctv in lake 
charles la for 18 million from g russell chambers 
nasco later sued accusing chambers of breaking the contract 
a federal judge ruled that chambers acted in bad faith in 
conducting his defense in the suit and in 1989 ordered chambers to 
pay about 1 million in legal fees to nasco 
the ruling was upheld in february by the 5th us circuit court 
of appeals 
in his appeal to the supreme court chambers said louisiana 
state law provided no basis for the attorney fee award he said the 
award was unreasonable and violated his rights 
the case is chambers vs nasco 90256 
