in 1987 setting requirements for nursing homes to follow to 
participate in the medicare and medicaid programs 
those include provisions on quality of living conditions access 
to social activities accommodation of personal needs assessments 
for health care services protection of residents personal funds 
and privacy 
other provisions require confidentiality of medical records 
limitations on the use of physical and chemical restraints choice 
of personal attending physicians and access to telephones 
some of the regulations to implement the new requirements are in 
place but nursing home owners have complained that regulations for 
critical provisions of the law have not been issued 
gail wilensky head of the health care financing administration 
which handles medicare and medicaid said the majority of the 
regulations were in place and those that arent yet final soon will 
be 
states consumer groups and nursing home industry groups have 
been consulted and have been fully informed of the new requirements 
as we have developed and issued guidelines instructions and 
regulations during the past three years she said 
in a petition to the department of health and human services 
the american health care association said many states have not 
allocated adequate funds to implement the law 
the association representing 10000 nursing homes asked 
wilenskys agency to issue regulatory guidance to the states 
outlining what actions the federal government will take to ensure 
that state plans are funded 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

