trial on misdemeanor charges of pandering obscenity and using 
children in nudityrelated material 
if convicted of both charges barrie could be sentenced to one 
year in jail and fined 2000 the gallery could be fined 10000 
for conviction on both counts 
the prosecution completed its case after questioning its third 
witness and entering the photographs into evidence all of the 
witnesses were police officers 
after prosecutors rested judge david albanese rejected a 
defense request to dismiss the charges and the defense began to 
present witnesses 
the seven photographs were among 175 pictures in an exhibit 
called robert mapplethorpe the perfect moment the sevenweek 
exhibit drew 80000 people before it ended may 26 
five of the photographs show sexually graphic acts involving 
men and two are of children whose genitals are exposed 
prosecutors contend all that is necessary for a conviction under 
ohio obscenity law is to prove the photos were displayed 
the bottom line is the pictures were not required to show 
contemporary community standards because the court determines 
that prosecutor frank prouty said 
the prosecution entered the photographs into evidence over 
defense lawyers objections they argued that the photos were being 
taken out of context and should be presented as part of the entire 
exhibit as they were displayed 
during questioning of the first defense witness defense lawyer 
marc mezibov gave the photos to jurors to help them understand 
remarks by the woman who assembled the exhibit 
janet kardon former director of the university of 
pennsylvanias institute of contemporary art testified that she 
worked closely with mapplethorpe in choosing photographs for the 
exhibit she said the 175 photos were culled from more than 2000 
and that each was chosen for its artistic merit 
we looked for a body of work that has consistency saying 
something that is important to say ms kardon said 
she said she felt an urgency to put the exhibit together between 
april 1987 and december 1988 because mapplethorpe was dying of 
aids he died in boston in march 1989 at age 42 
he was one of the most important photographers working in the 
80s i felt it was my responsibility as a curator to work with him 
while he was alive ms kardon said 
when asked by prosecutors to describe the artistic merit of four 
photos depicting sexually explicit acts ms kardon said they were 
artistically lighted and framed and showed symmetry and use of 
horizontal and vertical lines 
jacquelynn baas director of the university of californias art 
museum referred to texture and effectiveness of expression in 
describing the same photos 
robert mapplethorpe was an artist who set out very consciously 
and with a great deal of courage to create a wide range of art 
he very consciously explored what makes a work of art a very 
powerful experience she said 
barries lawyer h louis sirkin told jurors that the gallery 
director and its officers knew the exhibit would be controversial 
but he said they believed the educational and cultural value 
outweighed other considerations and was consistent with the 
gallerys mission to display contemporary art 
there was controversy but there was only one intent and 
purpose to add to the cultural enhancement of the citizens of 
this city and this area sirkin said 
it was brought here not to appeal to anyones prurient 
interest he said it was brought here to teach and to show 
the world this brilliant photographer and some of the inner makings 
of that man and some of the torture that perhaps he suffered 
</TEXT>
