a typical new england household used 736 gallons of home heating 
oil in the winter of 1987 the latest for which figures are 
available said tom welch of the energy information administration 
the increased tax would add 1472 to the cost of that much fuel 
oil 
in 1988 average gasoline consumption per household was 917 
gallons in the northeast 1016 gallons in the midwest and 1046 
gallons in the south and west welch said 
based on those figures the average driver in the northeast 
would pay 11004 more each year with the gasoline tax increase a 
midwest driver would pay 12192 more while one in the west or 
south would pay 12552 more 
the tax on home heating oil is expected to yield the government 
200 million over five years the gasoline tax is expected to bring 
in 45 billion in that period 
both fuels have seen sharp price runups since the aug 2 
takeover of kuwait by iraq 
