<TEXT>
a former san jose calif city council member 
who won and then lost a 101 million libel award against his 
local newspaper lost a supreme court appeal oct 1 
the court without comment let stand rulings that claude 
fletcher failed to prove the san jose mercury news published 
statements about him with actual malice knowledge or reckless 
disregard of their falsity 
fletcher sued the mercury news over a series of 1984 articles 
reporting on his conduct while a city council member and as a board 
member of a local antipoverty agency 
fletchers 1984 bid for reelection failed after the articles 
were published the articles reported that five agency officials 
said fletcher tried to steer a 16 million contract to an 
insulation business in which he became a partner 
the articles quoted the agencys executive director as saying 
fletcher once offered him and his wife a trip to hawaii which the 
agency official interpreted as a bribe 
a jury in 1986 awarded fletcher 250000 in general damages 
25000 in special damages and 735000 in punitive damages 
but the trial judge threw out the award ruling fletcher had 
failed to prove the articles were published with actual malice a 
burden facing any public official who sues for libel 
a state appeals court upheld the dismissal of the award and the 
california supreme court refused to hear fletchers appeal last 
february 
in its 1989 ruling the appeals court said the evidence 
suggests a sincere attempt to report what the mercury news viewed 
as unethical behavior on the part of a san jose public official 
it added clearly the articles contained factual errors but 
was there clear and convincing evidence that the papers reporter 
did not believe his story was true we do not think so 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the supreme court refused oct 1 to let the 
st louis postdispatch see some confidential documents in the 
governments corruption investigation of pentagon contracts 
the court over two dissenting votes let stand a ruling that 
the privacy rights of mcdonnell douglas corp the nations largest 
defense contractor and some of its employees outweigh the publics 
right to know more about the weapons procurement case 
justices byron r white and harry a blackmun voted to hear 
arguments in the case but four votes are needed to grant such 
review 
the justice department investigation called operation ill 
wind began in 1987 and has yielded more than three dozen guilty 
pleas or convictions on fraud and briberyrelated charges 
among the contractors investigated was mcdonnell douglas which 
is based in the st louis area and receives some 9 billion a year 
in pentagon contracts 
the fbi in 1988 conducted a search of defense contractor 
offices including those of mcdonnell douglas and its vice 
president thomas gunn search warrants were based on information 
the fbi obtained listening to wiretapped telephone conversations 
the postdispatch asked to see sealed documents related to the 
warrants particularly government affidavits that might reveal what 
was learned by listening to the wiretaps 
the justice department initially opposed making the documents 
public but substantially dropped its opposition in december 1988 
the government now siding with the newspaper said it no longer 
had a compelling interest in keeping portions of the material 
secret since it had concluded part of the investigation 
but mcdonnell douglas gunn and five unidentified employees 
continued to oppose disclosure 
a federal judge ordered parts of the documents unsealed but the 
ruling was reversed in february by the 8th us circuit court of 
appeals 
the appeals court said the absence of an indictment against the 
company and its employees weighs heavily in favor of the privacy 
interests and nondisclosure 
these search warrant affidavits implicate some individuals 
directly in criminal misconduct others only indirectly the 
appeals court said disclosure could seriously damage their 
reputations and careers 
</TEXT>
