<TEXT>
reporters cant be jailed for refusing to 
provide notes photos or news sources to people who sue one another 
based on an eventthe reporter covered the state supreme court 
ruled sept 27 
californias press shield law which forbids holding reporters 
in contempt for withholding confidential sources or unpublished 
material provides ironclad protection in civil cases the court 
said in a unanimous decision 
the shield law was made part of the state constitution by the 
voters in 1980 in response to the jailing of several reporters for 
refusing to reveal their sources 
the court ruled in may that in criminal cases reporters can be 
required to testify or provide evidence if necessary to protect a 
defendants constitutional right to a fair trial but the justices 
ruled sept 27 that parties to a civil suit have no similar 
constitutional right that can overcome the shield law 
this is a complete victory for the journalists and the 
public said c michael cooney lawyer for new york times co 
publisher of the santa barbara newspress the case arose when an 
automobile company sued in a 1984 accident sought a newspress 
photographers pictures of the crash 
michael zuk lawyer for the company volkswagen of america said 
the ruling would deny my client access to what may be critical 
evidence in civil litigation the voters who passed the shield 
law did not intend to foreclose any evidence held by reporters that 
could be essential to a civil suit he argued 
the rulings main impact is on civil suits that do not directly 
involve the news media in which evidence is sought from a 
reporter if the reporter cannot be held in contempt of court and 
jailed until he or she testifies there is little a judge or a 
party to a suit can do to compel the testimony 
the opinion by justice david eagleson said the party seeking the 
evidence could sue the reporter under a law providing a 500 
penalty plus actual damages caused by a witness refusal to provide 
evidence but eagleson said the law was rarely used and would be 
virtually ineffectual in compelling testimony 
in a case that has a news organization as a party such as a 
libel suit the ruling has a lesser impact because judges can take 
other steps against parties who withhold evidence such as deciding 
the case in the opponents favor 
</TEXT>
