family traditions collecting fine objects and adding on to their 
mansion 
t harrison garrett bought carefully but even so his 
collections had outgrown evergreen house a few years after he moved 
in in 1878 he either had to stop buying the coins rare books 
prints and manuscripts or build more rooms 
so he added on and on a wing here a library there servants 
quarters and reading rooms 
sixty years and a few generations later the classic revival 
house ended up as 48 rooms with a separate wing for the gymnasium 
school room and bowling alley 
there are other big houses in the united states this is a 
little bit different because the house actually grew out of the 
collections said susan g tripp director of university 
collections at johns hopkins university which owns the museum 
as the collections grew they loved adding to the house to house 
the collections 
the house museum reopened to the public last month after a 
threeyear 43 million renovation to replace the heating air 
conditioning wiring plumbing and roof the furniture was 
refurbished by sothebys restorations 
the yellow mansion is a fine example of the way people of wealth 
and culture lived in the early days of the 20th century in the 
midatlantic region tripp said 
the garretts immense wealth was built on commerce and 
investment banking two generations of garretts served as president 
of the baltimore amp ohio railroad 
the familys passion for beauty and the arts is evidenced by 
their collection of tiffany light fixtures and glassware a theater 
decorated by russian designer leon bakst and a collection of dutch 
marquetry furniture from the 18th and 19th centuries 
the former bowling alley is a gallery for an extensive display 
of netsuke inro and lacquer boxes 18th and 19thcentury chinese 
snuff bottles chinese ceramics dating from 200 bc and japanese 
ceramics from the 18th to 19th centuries 
exhibition rooms on the second floor display a comprehensive 
collection of tiffany and steuben glass rookwood pottery and 16 
paintings by dufy works by modigliani degas and vuillard are 
scattered throughout the mansion 
the house boasts a splendid bathroom where the window frame 
shutters cabinet and water tank are gilded with 23 carat gold 
leaf the floors walls and ceilings were finished in a marble 
mosaic 
people who visit love to see the grandeur of a house people 
come to see not so much each object but the house as a whole 
said tripp 
john work garrett a career diplomat who inherited the house in 
1920 continued the family traditions of collecting and enlarging 
the house until he died in 1942 
john work garrett originally was motivated to be a collector 
of books and coins said james garrett of baltimore the 
grandnephew of john work garrett and a member of the board of the 
evergreen foundation he was particularly interested in books 
that dealt with the natural world they had a real appreciation and 
desire to preserve wonderful things 
the estate is tucked away on 50 acres in the city a few blocks 
from johns hopkins university the property and its collections 
were given to the university on garretts death 
the renovation was carried out in a sensitive way to the 
intent of the wills of the last residents that is be used for 
future generations garrett said 
their motivation would have been for developing a collection 
which would be available to share he said throughout their 
lives they didnt specifically open the doors to the city but 
they did share their things with friends and acquaintances they 
did have performances by various theater and music groups that 
sometimes were in residence so they opened the house up to others 
in that way 
they were very thoughtful in what they chose to add to the 
collection the chinese and japanese works being an example and 
specific in certain areas of the book collection 
the reading room added in 1885 contains painted panels 
depicting each of john work garretts diplomatic postings rome 
berlin the hague paris rome argentina venezuela luxembourg 
and washington 
he was interested in early voyages and travels he collected 
the maps the explorers used he was a very fussy collector people 
asked why he didnt have a gutenberg he had looked for a wonderful 
copy but it was a continual search for best one said jane katz 
assistant director of museums for johns hopkins 
alice warder garrett johns wife had a passion for the visual 
and performing arts under her direction the gymnasium was turned 
into a theater designed by bakst a russian artist who dazzled 
europe with his imaginative costume and set designs for the ballet 
russe it is the only surviving theater designed by bakst 
the designs on the walls the stage sets and decorations belong 
to what is considered one of the largest and most important private 
collections of baksts works he decorated the walls and ceilings 
with stencils based on russian peasant motifs 
