<TEXT>
nobody from the lost generation of american 
expatriate writers has been more lost than robert mcalmon 
he squandered fame fortune and friends during the 1920s in 
paris he lost the manuscript of his major work family 
panorama and practically all his belongings fleeing the nazi 
occupation in 1940 and somewhere near oblivion mcalmon lost his 
life to alcohol at desert hot springs calif on feb 2 1956 
mcalmon the last of the lost is the one whose life most 
exactly fulfilled gertrude steins prophecy that his generation was 
indeed lost 
but as ernest hemingway replied to stein the sun also 
rises it is rising finally for mcalmon 35 years after his death 
with the publication for the first time in the united states of his 
two surviving novels village and postadolescence 
the university of new mexico press with the prodding and 
editing of english doctoral candidate edward ns lorusso sold out 
it first printing of village in a few months this summer and 
is going into a second printing postadolescence and about 20 
mcalmon short stories will be published next year 
at this point mcalmon is a discovery lorusso says most 
people have only known him as a footnote to the story of the lost 
generation more of a social figure than a literary figure and 
that may change 
the spare straightforward village is a series of loosely 
linked sketches set in the fictional town of wentworth nd 
around the turn of the century turning the century is precisely 
what mcalmon set out to do lorusso says 
there is a difference between village and winesburg ohio 
or main street that really does give mcalmon the edge he says 
he has one foot in the 20th century i think while sinclair 
lewis and sherwood anderson are still sort of 19th century in 
their approaches theres sentimentality and a lot of judgment and 
direction on how the reader should feel about characters which 
mcalmon doesnt do and which hemingway also went on not to do 
its left to the reader to make those kinds of decisions and i 
think mcalmon might really have been the starting point of that 
like many american towns wentworth is made up of disparate 
desperate people who somehow nonetheless have a collective 
conscience consciousness and will mcalmons eye roves from family 
to clique quirk to eccentricity 
having grown up in a town very similar to the wentworth of 
village i think he mcalmon is very conscious of this fact that 
the individual is robbed of his or her individuality because of 
this collective consciousness 
mcalmon was born on march 9 1896 in clifton kan son of an 
irishborn presbyterian minister and the youngest of eight 
children the family moved from town to town and stayed mainly 
poor says mcalmons nephew george mcalmon an attorney in el 
paso texas 
village thats the family thats autobiographical as far 
as i can tell george mcalmon says 
as a young man robert went to new york and became an artists 
model there he met and married british heiress winifred ellerman 
who wrote under the pen name of bryher an odd marriage as bryher 
was an acknowledged lesbian when they divorced mcalmon received a 
large settlement which enabled him to establish a small publishing 
business in paris during the early 20s 
if he has his rightful place its more often given him as a 
publisher than as a writer lorusso says he did publish 
hemingways three stories and ten poems he did publish steins 
the making of americans he did publish other things by hd 
hilda doolittle william carlos williams and nathanael west its 
easy to see yes he was the one who started these people and got 
them into print first 
but as a writer i think this is where he is likely to be some 
kind of a discovery 
lorusso says the missing body of mcalmons work including 
dozens of short stories must be resurrected in print so his proper 
place in literature can be assessed 
i think at that point we can decide objectively whether or not 
mcalmon was the beginning of the whole new literary tradition the 
break from the 19th century the break from the british english so 
commonly used by people like henry james and edith wharton 
his own generation of writers with a few exceptions already 
had relegated him to a literary scrapheap even though he had given 
so many of them money food and their first break 
it had been mcalmon who paid for hemingways 1923 trip to spain 
from which emerged the sun also rises he helped james joyce 
type ulysses editing and rearrangingportions of molly blooms 
concluding streamofconsciousness soliloquy 
he literally supported joyce for a long period of time 
lorusso says 
but when mcalmon wrote a memoir about the paris period being 
geniuses together joyce called it the office boys revenge 
and when f scott fitzgerald learned that charles scribners 
sons might consider publishing mcalmons family panorama he 
wrote to scribners editor maxwell perkins advising him to pass 
by the way fitzgeralds letter says mcalmon is a bitter 
rat and im not surprised at anything he does or says hes failed 
as a writer and tries to fortify himself by tying up to the big 
boys like joyce and stein and despising everyone else part of his 
quarrel with ernest hemingway some years ago was because he 
assured ernest that i was a fairy god knows he shows more 
creative imagination in his malice than in his work next he told 
morley callaghan that ernest was a fairy hes a pretty good 
person to avoid 
perkins passed 
all those people he literally supported turned on him 
lorusso says 
what was it about mcalmon anyway 
honesty says lorusso because he was willing to look 
objectively at people around him including himself 
generosity 
i think its like with any kind of handout says lorusso 
maybe at first youre appreciative of it then after a while you 
become resentful 
mcalmon had money mcalmon had a press plus with his own 
personality he ended up alienating just about everybody when he 
tried to establish a foothold in america to try to get some of his 
work published here it all worked against him 
after mcalmon returned to the united states in 1940 with little 
more than the clothes he wore he took a job in his uncles medical 
supply business in el paso 
he got out of europe just ahead of the germans nephew 
george mcalmon says at that time i was 16 i knew him pretty 
well he had a drinking problem all those guys writers they 
either went to aa or they died from it he died from it 
it was a sad existence for him he wasnt doing any 
literary work he went downhill lost a lot of interest his 
friends died i remember him commenting on when james joyce died 
he moved to california in 1953 to be near his sister victoria 
less than three years later he was dead 
