here are some of the countries hit 
hardest by the persian gulf crisis and their economic prospects 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
turkey as one of the socalled frontline states it will lose 
an estimated 7 billion because of higher oil prices and reduced 
exports and tourism by the end of next year turkey got 60 percent 
of its oil from neighboring iraq before the crisis and earned 300 
million a year from iraq in oil pipeline fees 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
india india will lose 35 billion this year said a senior 
foreign ministry official in new delhi that includes 1 billion 
spent evacuating indian nationals from iraq and kuwait half the 
185000 indians in the two countries have been repatriated so far 
the cost of oil imports 40 percent of which came from iraq and 
kuwait will rise by 15 billion to 6 billion a year that will 
drive the balance of payments deficit to a critical 55 billion 
fuel prices were raised by 20 percent shortly before the crisis 
broke and another increase is expected 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the philippines few statistics are yet available but merill 
lynch said in its monthly asian commentary that the philippines 
economy will likely be the hardest hit in the far east manila 
imports all its oil and high prices mean a severe drain on its 
foreign currency reserves inflation is expected to increase by as 
much as 5 percent to 1618 percent this year 
more than 15000 of the estimated 93000 filipinos in kuwait and 
iraq have been repatriated and thousands more are expected to need 
return home apart from the loss of remittances the returning 
nationals will push up unemployment past the current 8 percent 
total 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
egypt officials expect egypt can weather the crisis provided 
aid is forthcoming although it has a 50 billion debt prime 
minister atef sedki has estimated losses at 45 billion including 
24 billion in remittances from the 1 millionplus egyptians who 
worked in kuwait and iraq 
that total does not count 10 billion to 12 billion egyptians 
lost in kuwait banks looted by the iraqis or writing off 446 
million owed by iraq 
however egypt will earn an extra 1 billion this fiscal year 
from oil exports president bush has asked congress to write off 
egypts 67 billion foreign debt 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
brazil soaring oil prices mean its import bill could double to 
6 billion a year that will make it harder to pay off brazils 
117 billion debt fuel price increases will push up the cost of 
living and there is already speculation of rationing which would 
slow down the economy 
brazil was iraqs closest ally in south america but economic 
and military links have been sharply reduced brazil has not sold 
weapons to iraq since 1988 because of debts on previous arms sales 
unofficially estimated at 3 billion 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
romania officials estimate the crisis will cost 3 billion 
including writing off iraqs 17 billion debt baghdad was to 
repay 70 percent of that in cheap oil now romania its soviet 
supplies curtailed will have to pay out an estimated 770 million 
officials estimate that contracts with iraq worth 12 billion 
have been lost 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
czechoslovakia the embargo will cost czechoslovakia an 
estimated 1 billion and it will have to write off iraqs 17 
billion debt mostly for arms purchases the loss of these sales 
will deprive the country of sorely needed foreign currency to buy 
oil after the soviets slashed deliveries by 18 million barrels this 
year 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
poland warsaw has told the un security council the crisis has 
caused serious social and economic problems iraq was polands 
biggest trading partner in the middle east losses will total about 
24 billion for a country saddled with a 42 billion foreign debt 
warsaw was owed 500 million by iraq mainly for arms purchases 
and cancelled contracts amount to 15 billion iraq was polands 
main source of oil after the soviet union 
already hit by recession because of tough economic reforms 
poland is highly vulnerable to high oil prices 
