<TEXT>
china will harvest a record 422 million tons of 
grain this year providing the economys lone bright spot amid poor 
factory output and growing government debt official reports said 
monday 
the china daily quoted agriculture vice minister chen yaobang as 
saying the grain crop will be about 15 million tons over last 
years record 407 million tons 
he said good harvests also are exected in cotton edible oils 
and sugar 
chens announcement comes as good news to the communist party 
leadership which typically emphasizes grain production on the 
premise that a wellfed population is its best guarantee of staying 
in power 
during the past 18 months the party has been under particular 
stress from the collapse of communist rule in the east bloc 
demands for greater democracy at home and deep divisions among 
party leaders on how to respond 
determined to maintain stability in the countryside at least 
the government last spring increased investment in land reclamation 
and irrigation and made more credit available to farmers it 
recentralized the sale of fertilizer and pesticides which had been 
sold on the free market and were becoming expensive as demand drove 
up prices 
the government also renewed its insistence that farmers plant 
more grain and fewer vegetables and other crops grain production 
slumped in the mid and late 1980s because farmers found they could 
earn more by planting other crops 
this summer the government announced plans to raise its grain 
purchase price but did not say by how much 
it also said the state would buy the entire grain harvest a 
practice abandoned in the 1980s in recent years the state 
contracted with each farmer to buy part of his harvest leaving him 
free to sell the rest on the free market for a potentially higher 
price the arrangement was considered a first step toward market 
reform 
however the china daily said the government feared farmers 
would not get good prices on the free market this year because the 
supply of grain was so plentiful and that would discourage them 
from planting grain next spring 
so far the government has not announced any increase in the 
price at which it sells grain to city residents which has remained 
unchanged for 25 years city dwellers pay about 2 cents a pound 
about oneseventh of what the state pays the farmers 
subsidizing grain has become a major drain on the state budget 
the china daily recently said that by western accounting methods 
the budget deficit this year will total 9 billion 
stateowned industry has become another drain with profits down 
more than 50 percent from last years level a record number of 
state factories are reported in the red 
