<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to resolve a 
dispute from arkansas over the power of states to tax cable 
television companies and subscribers 
the court said it will review a ruling that arkansas may tax 
cable tv as long as it also imposes the levy on similar 
communication services such as the unscrambling of satellite 
signals 
with millions of dollars in tax revenue at stake the ruling was 
challenged in separate appeals by both the state and cable 
operators and subscribers 
arkansas in 1987 imposed its sales tax on cable tv service the 
law did not apply to those who own satellite dishes and subscribe 
to services that unscramble satellite signals 
also exempted from the tax were all newspaper sales and magazine 
subscription sales 
the arkansas supreme court ruled in february that the tax 
unlawfully discriminated against cable tv service because satellite 
service was excludedbut the state court said it is permissible 
for the state to exclude the newspaper and magazine sales 
we are unwilling to hold that all mass communications media 
must be taxed in the same way the state court said we must 
however hold that a tax which discriminates between mass 
communicators delivering the same service runs afoul of the first 
amendment guarantee of free expression 
by the time the state court ruled the arkansas legislature had 
amended the law to extend the tax to satellite service and all 
other distribution of television video or audio services with or 
without the use of wires 
the state court ordered arkansas officials to refund to cable 
operators and subscribers more than 8 million in taxes paid prior 
to enactment of the amended tax 
state officials seeking to avoid the refunds asked the us 
supreme court to overrule the state court decision 
the cable operators and subscribers also appealed urging the 
high court to issue a more sweeping decision that the state may not 
single out the electronic media for taxation when print media are 
exempt 
the justices in 1987 in a case from arkansas said states 
generally may not tax some types of publications while exempting 
others 
the court by a 72 vote struck down an arkansas sales tax 
imposed on general interest magazines but which exempted newspapers 
and religious professional trade and sports journals 
the cases acted on today are pledger vs medlock 9029 and 
medlock vs pledger 9038 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP901001-0265 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether oklahoma may collect a sales tax on cigarettes and other 
items sold at a shawnee convenience store owned and run by an 
indian tribe 
the justices said they will review a ruling that would bar the 
imposition of such a tax 
asked for its views the bush administration advised the 
justices to send the case back to a federal appeals court for 
further study the justices ignored that advice 
the store belongs to the citizen band potawatomi indian tribe 
and is located on land held in trust for the tribe by the federal 
government 
oklahoma law requires all vendors to collect from consumers 
sales taxes of 6 or 7 percent 4 percent for the state and 2 or 3 
percent for local communities 
the state also imposes an excise tax on the sale of cigarettes 
the potawatomis have never collected sales taxes or the 
cigarette excise tax on items sold in their convenience store in 
1987 state officials assessed the tribe 27 million for the sale 
and distribution of untaxed cigarettes 
the tribe challenged the assessment in court and us district 
judge lee r west blocked enforcement of the cigarette tax pending 
the tribes lawsuit 
west later ruled that cigarettes sold to tribal members could 
not be taxed but that the tribe must collect taxes on cigarettes 
sold to nonmembers 
but the 10th us circuit court of appeals last november ruled 
that the tribe does not have to collect any state or local taxes on 
items sold at the store even to nonmembers 
the appeals court said oklahoma officials wrongly relied on a 
1980 supreme court ruling in a washington state case to justify the 
taxing of sales to nontribal members 
in the 1980 case the appeals court said the indian tribe had 
opted to come under state jurisdiction it said because no 
such jurisdiction exists in this case oklahomas reliance on the 
1980 decision is misplaced 
in the appeal acted on today oklahoma officials said the 
case turns on whether federal law has preempted state law or 
whether state action has infringed tribal selfgovernment 
the appeal added the state simply suggests that the tribe may 
operate its government in any way that it sees fit however if the 
tribe operates a business in the state it must obey applicable 
state laws 
the case is oklahoma tax commission vs citizen band potawatomi 
indian tribe 891322 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP901001-0266 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether savings and loan associations and other financial 
institutions may claim tax deductions for reciprocal sales of 
mortgage loans 
with a reported 419 million plus interest at stake the court 
said it will hear internal revenue service arguments against 
allowing such deductions 
two federal appeals courts have ruled against the irs and one 
has ruled for the tax agency the justices decision expected by 
july will resolve the conflicting rulings 
an irs victory would mean more bad news for some struggling 
sampls 
in the lead case granted review today a greenville texas 
savings and loan challenged an irs refusal to treat the sale of its 
mortgage loans to another sampl as a transaction that generated a 
loss for tax purposes 
centennial savings bank formerly known as first federal savings 
and loan of greenville entered into a deal with another savings 
and loan in which it sold a package of interests in a group of 
residential mortgage loans for a similar package of mortgage loan 
interests 
the thrifts were taking advantage of a rule adopted in 1980 by 
the federal home loan bank board allowing reciprocal sales of 
depreciated substantially identical mortgage loans without 
having to record a loss for regulatory accounting purposes 
the rule allowed savings institutions to engage in transactions 
to generate deductible losses for federal tax purposes without 
worrying about failing to meet the bank boards minimum reserve and 
liquidity requirements 
in 1981 centennials mortgage loan portfolio was comprised 
primarily of longterm home mortgage loans that had been issued in 
the late 1960s at fixed interest rates significantly lower than 
current rates 
because of the low interest they earned the fair market value 
of these older loans fell far below their face amount 
centennial had a tax incentive for disposing of the old mortgage 
loans selling them would enable it to realize a tax loss based on 
the difference between the face amounts and the sale prices of the 
mortgages it sold 
after the irs ruled that centennial could not claim a tax 
deduction for the transaction the savings and loan paid its 
assessed taxes and sued for a refund a federal judge ruled for the 
government but the new orleansbased 5th us circuit court of 
appeals last november reversed the judges ruling 
the appeals court also ruled in cases involving savings and 
loans from san antonio and temple texas 
in seeking supreme court review government lawyers noted that 
the cincinnatibased 6th us circuit court of appeals had ruled 
that such transactions do not result in taxdeductible losses 
that case involves the cottage savings association of 
cincinnati 
the irs has advised that there are currently pending 
administratively and in the courts 96 cases involving approximately 
419 million excluding interest that turn on the resolution of 
the mortgage exchange issue the governments appeal in the 
centennial case said 
while the dispute was pending before the 5th circuit court 
centennial was found insolvent by the bank board and the federal 
savings and loan insurance corporation was appointed as receiver 
the successor resolution trust corp then took over as receiver 
the cases are us vs centennial savings bank 891926 and 
cottage savings association vs commissioner internal revenue 
891965 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

