<DOCNO> AP901001-0280 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the nations manufacturing economy last month 
hit its lowest level since the end of the previous recession in 
late 1982 according to a key business survey released monday 
the third straight monthly drop in the national association of 
purchasing management index provided more evidence of an imminent 
recession and reflected increased prices from the persian gulf 
crisis 
the group said its indexes for production new orders imports 
inventories and employment all dropped sharply last month 
meanwhile its price index shot up to its highest level since 
september 1988 
coupled with sharply rising prices for petroleumrelated 
products spawned by the middle east crisis the immediate outlook 
appears to be the worst of all combinations a declining economy 
with rising inflation said robert j bretz chairman of the 
groups business survey committee 
the groups purchasing managers index which tracks overall 
business activity at 300 industrial companies fell to 444 
percent down sharply from 470 percent in august a reading below 
50 indicates the manufacturing economy is declining 
septembers reading was the lowest since 428 percent in 
december 1982 the first month of the current economic expansion 
the index stood at 460 percent a year ago 
in other economic news the government reported that 
construction spending stalled in august after posting its first 
gain in four months in july sagging consumer confidence and the 
gulf crisis were to blame analysts said 
a real estate trade group said the average american familys 
ability to buy a home improved in august thanks to a combination 
of falling prices lower mortgage rates and rising incomes but the 
national association of realtors said the improvement was curtailed 
by the gulf crisis and the general weakness of the economy 
the purchasing management report although grim helped spark a 
rally in the stock market coupled with the longawaited federal 
budget accord announced over the weekend the report raised hopes 
that the federal reserve would finally allow interest rates to 
decline 
david wyss chief economist with drimcgraw hill inc in 
lexington mass said the purchasing management figures were not 
surprising because the manufacturing sector has been slumping for 
more than a year but he added that right now were looking for 
evidence of recession and this is certainly one more bit 
the manufacturing sector has been in what some economists label 
a recession because of a decline in consumer purchases of durable 
goods such as automobiles a slowdown in nondefense capital goods 
purchases and a decline in defense spending 
new orders by companies fell for the third straight month to 
445 percent from 464 percent in august the lowest level since 
november 1982 at the trough of the recession 
thirty percent of those businesses surveyed said their new 
orders declined from august while 23 percent said they were better 
and 47 percent unchanged 
the groups production index fell to 451 percent from 485 
percent in august its lowest level since december 1982 a total of 
29 percent of those surveyed said production declined while 23 
percent said it increased and 48 percent reported no change 
the imports index fell to 455 percent from 475 percent its 
lowest level in nine months new export orders though increased 
for the 33rd straight month with the index up to 540 percent from 
530 percent 
but wyss said even the exports sector is likely to be pinched in 
the coming months now with the oil shock hitting the rest of the 
world too that is likely to be slowing down he said 
inventories declined in septmeber for the 22nd straight month 
while supplier deliveries were slightly faster indicating a 
declining economy 
prices shot up with 50 percent of those surveyed reporting 
increases against just 6 percent reporting decreases the price 
index leaped to 734 percent in septemer from 582 percent in 
august the biggest onemonth gain since august 1975 
meanwhile the groups employment index declined for the 19th 
straight month at its greatest rate in five years adding to the 
sectors woes 
the group said purchasers were concerned suppliers would use 
uncertainty from the middle east crisis to raise prices more even 
when increases are not warranted 
in a special question on capital spending plans for the next six 
to 12 months 88 percent of respondents said their plans had not 
changed because of the gulf standoff 8 percent said they were 
revised downward and 4 percent revised upward 
