around washington legislators lobbyists and 
public interest groups looked monday at the plan to cut government 
spending with the foreboding of a motorist receiving his mechanics 
estimate 
they knew it would be costly but not exactly how costly 
the 500 billion dent the government plans to make in its red 
ink the next five years will trickle up from many streams small and 
large from a nickel from each gallon of gasoline at first to an 
added 570 a month for medicare from 134 billion in new taxes 
and fees to a 182 billion cutback in defense and domestic 
programs 
it starts with 40 billion in cutbacks the first year 
the broad targets are there but the details will have to be 
worked out 
heres a quick look at some of the prospects 
medicare 
the federal health care program for 33 million elderly and 
disabled americans would take the largest hit of any of the 
entitlement programs with a hopedfor reduction of 60 billion 
about half would come from recipients whose 2860 monthly 
premium for doctors care would increase to 3430 next year and 
whose 75 deductible on doctors bills would double by 1995 
the other half would come from cutting back on reimbursements to 
hospitals and physicians 
the 145 percent tax that helps support the medicare program 
would rise from the first 51300 of income to the first 73000 
groups representing the elderly cried foul arthur flemming 
head of the save our social security coalition said it was 
indefensible that the summiteers put half the revenue burden on 
medicare 
