exxon corp and its shipping subsidiary 
have filed notices of claims against the us coast guard totalling 
more than 2 billion in connection with the exxon valdez shipwreck 
exxon spokesman les rogers said the sept 21 filings satisfy an 
administrative requirement that preserves options for exxon and 
exxon shipping co to sue the coast guard over the spill 
exxon has said it has spent more than 2 billion for both its 
cleanup efforts and payments to fishermen and related businesses 
for losses related to the spill 
the claimants allege the coast guard is wholly or partially 
liable for costs exxon incurred in cleaning up the spill and for 
amounts paid to parties in settlement of claims as well as for 
future costs expected to be incurred by exxon as a result of 
pending litigation said coast guard cmdr john mcelwain 
exxon declined to offer an explanation for why company officials 
think the coast guard should share responsibility for the march 24 
1989 oil spill that dumped nearly 11 million gallons of crude into 
prince william sound 
but in the past exxon has claimed that the cleanup was hindered 
by cleanup authorities refusal to give it blanket permission to 
use dispersants in the first three days after the spill the coast 
guard was involved in the decision exxon has said broader use of 
the chemical would have kept more oil off the shores of the sound 
were trying to evaluate the claims against the coast guard 
to see if they have any basis in admiralty law mcelwain said 
some 200 civil lawsuits involving thousands of plaintiffs have 
been filed against exxon mostly in state court in alaska 
plaintiffs include the state residents of villages in the 
spills path fishermen fish processors tourism companies 
fishing lodges and some of the nations largest environmental 
organizations 
court dates have not been scheduled 
