<TEXT>
former treasury secretary donald t regan said 
monday the savings and loan industry would have plunged into the 
tank deeper and faster without the deregulatory policies of the 
reagan administration 
absolutely not regan replied when asked by rep chalmers 
wylie rohio if the thrift debacle discredited deregulation 
regan appeared before the house banking committee in the first of a 
series of hearings examining the causes of the sampl mess 
when you see the eastern european countries coming over 
here to find out how did we do it you have to say our policies 
were correct and deregulation was one of them said regan who 
served as treasury secretary from 1981 to 1985 when he became 
white house chief of staff 
regan said that after interest rates soared in the 1980s a 
result he said of the economic policies of the carter 
administration it became clear that a financial business confined 
to taking deposits from savers and lending the money to home buyers 
could not survive 
he said he had favored giving thrifts the same investment powers 
as commercial banks but had opposed the broader deregulation in 
some states that had given thrifts nonbank powers 
if not for the administrationbacked banking deregulation bill 
of 1982 i think the thrift industry would have gone into the 
tank sooner and may have never emerged he said 
regan who was chairman of merrill lynch before becoming 
treasury secretary was described as the father of brokered 
deposits by rep joseph kennedy dmass 
such highinterest deposits placed by wall street brokerage 
houses usually in amounts just under the 100000 deposit 
insurance limit are blamed for fueling the explosive growth in 
risky investments at many sampls 
regan however said he had recused himself from any policy 
matters affecting brokered deposits because of his connection to 
merrill lynch and said the firm did not deal in them extensively 
until after he left 
i want a blood test as far as being the father of brokered 
deposits i am not in no way shape or fashion he said 
kennedy countered that regan allowed his subordinate deputy 
treasury secretary rt mcnamar to forcefully advocate their use 
regan blamed the explosion of brokered deposits on congress 
1980 decision to raise the deposit insurance limit from 40000 per 
account to 100000 as a reform he advocated forcing depositors 
to pay for their own deposit insurance on amounts over 100000 
edwin gray the nations top thrift regulator from 1983 to 1987 
has accused regan of trying to force him from office when he tried 
to rein in the industry in general and brokered deposits in 
particular 
regan who previously had not had a chance to reply to gray in a 
public forum described him as an absentee lax regulator 
in 1985 when i became chief of staff i began to hear rumors 
that this man was not paying attention he was part of the problem 
not the solution he was sort of a front for the industry i 
didnt like that regan said 
he sid that between september 1983 and june 1986 gray was in 
his office only 397 weekdays and absent 466 days he also noted 
that gray was forced to repay his agency the federal home loan 
bank board 26000 for travel and entertainment 
he want to pebble beach he went to greenbriar my crack was 
i think hes working more on his handicap than hes working on the 
thrifts regan said adding later this guy gets religion when 
hes found out 
gray and former federal reserve board chairman paul volcker are 
scheduled to appear before the committee wednesday the committee 
chairman rep henry b gonzalez dtexas plans to hear from 
carter administration officials later richard t pratt grays 
predecessor at the bank board from 1981 to 1983 testified after 
regan 
pratt said he was rejected by congress and the reagan 
administration in his attempts to get money to pay for more sampl 
examiners regan he said would not take his calls 
pratt also defended his decision early in the sampl crisis to 
permit thrifts to use accounting techniques to hide their losses 
otherwise it would have cost 178 billion 350 billion in 1990 
dollars to liquidate insolvent thrifts he said 
pratt said when he took office nearly every sampl in the nation 
was technically insolvent because soaring interest rates had 
drastically cut the value of their lowinterest fixedrate 
mortgages regulators strategy was to close the worst institutions 
and to buy time for the others until interest rates fell as they 
did he said 
