<TEXT>
the supreme court on monday agreed to decide 
whether workers who accuse employers of violating a federal law 
against age discrimination sometimes may be forced to submit their 
case to arbitration 
the justices said they will hear an appeal by a north carolina 
man fired at age 62 by a securities firm 
robert gilmer was fired in 1987 as manager of financial services 
for interstatejohnson lane corp and was replaced by a 28yearold 
who gilmer said was less qualified 
six years earlier when he was hired gilmer signed a 
registration form as a securities representative with the new york 
stock exchange in which he agreed to submit any dispute between 
himself and his employer to arbitration 
the 4th us circuit court of appeals ruled in february that the 
arbitration agreement is binding 
gilmer said the agreement violates the federal age 
discrimination in employment act 
but the 4th circuit court said nothing in the law forbids 
arbitration congress clearly did not intend that all adea 
disputes be resolved in federal court the appeals court said it 
also noted that the supreme court in recent rulings has endorsed 
arbitration as an alternative to lawsuits in some cases 
the case is gilmer vs interstatejohnson lane 9018 
