<TEXT>
treasury bond prices surged monday as the market 
cheered a sharp drop in oil prices and the federal budget accord 
reached by congress and president bush over the weekend 
the bond market was kind of deluged with good news today 
said susan hering a treasury bond economist at salomon brothers 
inc 
the widely watched 30year treasury bond rose 1 132 point or 
1032 for every 1000 in face amount its yield which falls when 
the price rises dropped to 884 percent from 894 percent late 
friday it was the lowest yield for the long bond in about six 
weeks 
bond prices usually rise on signs that inflation may be easing 
one such signal is a drop in oil prices which bonds have tracked 
closely since iraqs aug 2 invasion of kuwait 
the november contract for oil dropped 242 a barrel to 3709 
on the new york mercantile exchange the secondlargest price drop 
since the start of the persian gulf crisis 
oil prices were influenced by a weekend statement from iraqi 
president saddam hussein that appeared to ease tensions in the 
middle east and by comments from bush who told the un general 
assembly on monday that he hoped there could be a diplomatic 
solution to the mideast turmoil 
meanwhile the bond market was encouraged by the accord on the 
fiscal 1991 federal budget the market has looked to the federal 
reserve to ease interest rates after the budget was resolved lower 
rates benefit fixedrate securities such as bonds 
william v sullivan director of money market research for dean 
witter reynolds inc attributed the sharp runup in bond prices to 
onethird budget twothirds oil 
it wasnt until the sharp plunge in oil following bushs 
united nations address that the bond market reenergized itself 
he said 
bond prices also were supported by another signal of growing 
weakness in the economy the nations corporate purchasing managers 
announced that their widely watched monthly index of industrial 
activity dropped for the third straight month to its lowest level 
in nearly eight years 
signs of economic sluggishness often are viewed favorably by 
bond investors because they may cause the fed to ease interest 
rates 
but ms hering wasnt optimistic that bond prices would retain 
their newfound strength she said the market remains tied to iraq 
and its effect on oil prices 
also monday the treasury sold at auction 92 billion in 
threemonth bills at an average discount rate of 718 percent and 
92 billion in sixmonth bills at an average discount rate of 721 
percent 
the rates were the lowest since threemonth bills sold for 717 
percent on sept 19 1988 and sixmonth bills averaged 719 
percent on aug 6 1990 
in the secondary market for treasury securities shortterm 
issues gained 332 point to 316 point intermediate maturities 
rose 1132 point to 1316 point and longterm issues jumped 2932 
point to 1 132 point according to telerate inc a financial 
information service 
the movement of a point is equivalent to a change of 10 in the 
price of a bond with a 1000 face value 
the shearson lehman brothers daily treasury bond index which 
measures price movements on all outstanding treasury issues with 
maturities of a year or longer advanced 361 to 115016 
yields on threemonth treasury bills were unchanged at 734 
percent as the discount remained at 712 percent yields on 
sixmonth bills fell marginally to at 7504 percent as the discount 
remained at 715 percent yields on oneyear bills fell to 761 
percent as the discount fell 5 basis points to 711 percent 
a basis point is onehundredth of a percentage point the yield 
is the annualized return on an investment in a treasury bill the 
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face 
value which is paid at maturity 
the federal funds rate the interest banks charge one another 
for overnight loans was quoted at 8 percent up from 8 percent 
late friday 
